# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: demographic-history-of-scotland
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen received royal burgh status from David I of Scotland (1124–1153), which transformed the city economically.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The traditional industries of fishing, paper-making, shipbuilding, and textiles have been overtaken by the oil industry and Aberdeen's seaport.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Heliport is one of the busiest commercial heliports in the world, and the seaport is the largest in the north-east part of Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A university town, the city is known for the University of Aberdeen, founded in 1495 as King's College, the fifth oldest university in the English-speaking world and located in Old Aberdeen.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the mid-18th to mid-20th centuries, Aberdeen's buildings incorporated locally quarried grey granite, which may sparkle like silver because of its high mica content.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Since the discovery of North Sea oil in 1969, Aberdeen has been known as the offshore **oil capital of Europe**.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Based upon the discovery of prehistoric villages around the mouths of the rivers Dee and Don, the area around Aberdeen is thought to have been settled for at least 6,000 years.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The name given to Aberdeen translates as 'mouth of the river Don', and is recorded as Aberdon in 1172 and Aberden in c.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The first element of the name is the Pictish word *aber* 'river mouth'.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The second element is from the Celtic river goddess Devona.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is usually described as within the historical Pictish territory and became Gaelic-speaking at some time in the medieval period.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Old Aberdeen is the approximate location of Aberdon, the first settlement of Aberdeen; this literally means "the mouth of the Don".
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Celtic word *aber* means "river mouth", as in modern Welsh (Aberystwyth, Aberdare, Aberbeeg etc.).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Gaelic name is *Obar Dheathain* (variation: *Obairreadhain*; **obar* presumably being a loan from the earlier Pictish; the Gaelic term is *inbhir*), and in Latin, the Romans referred to the river as *Devana*.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Medieval (or Ecclesiastical) Latin has it as *Aberdonia*.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The local Doric pronunciation, [ˌeːbərˈdin] ⓘ or [ˈeːbərdin] ⓘ (with a long *ay* sound), is frequently rendered *Aiberdeen* or *Aiberdein*.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen area has seen human settlement for at least 8,000 years.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city began as two separate burghs: Old Aberdeen at the mouth of the river Don; and New Aberdeen, a fishing and trading settlement, where the Denburn waterway entered the river Dee estuary.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The earliest charter was granted by William the Lion in 1179 and confirmed the corporate rights granted by David I.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1214, Aberdeen Burgesses were granted a Royal Charter by Alexander II of Scotland giving them the sole right to form a Guild.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This body exercised power in the composition of the local council, and the affairs of the town.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Burgesses of the Guild were an integral part of the council for more than 700 years and played a considerable role in the growth and development of Aberdeen.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1319, the Great Charter of Robert the Bruce transformed Aberdeen into a property-owning and financially independent community.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Granted with it was the nearby Forest of Stocket, whose income formed the basis for the city's Common Good Fund which still benefits Aberdonians.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of Scottish Independence, Aberdeen was under English rule, so Robert the Bruce laid siege to Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308, followed by executing the English garrison.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city was burned by Edward III of England in 1336, but was rebuilt and extended.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city was strongly fortified to prevent attacks by neighbouring lords, but the gates were removed by 1770.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's medieval council registers survive from 1398 onwards and are exceptional for their quantity and continuity among surviving Scottish burgh records.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The earliest eight volumes, from 1398 to 1511, have been included in the UNESCO UK Memory of the World Register, and have been edited in a digital edition.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the Wars of the Three Kingdoms of 1644 to 1647 the city was plundered by both sides.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1644, it was taken and ransacked by Royalist troops after the Battle of Aberdeen and two years later it was stormed by a Royalist force under the command of the George Gordon, 2nd Marquess of Huntly.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] An outbreak of bubonic plague over 1687 and 1688 killed 8.5% of the population, adding to the economic and demographic damage caused by war.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the 18th century, a new Town Hall was built and the first social services appeared with the Aberdeen Infirmary at Woolmanhill in 1739 and the Aberdeen Lunatic Asylum in 1800.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The expensive infrastructure works led to the city becoming bankrupt in 1817 during the Post-Napoleonic depression, an economic downturn immediately after the Napoleonic Wars; but the city's prosperity later recovered.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The increasing economic importance of Aberdeen and the development of the shipbuilding and fishing industries led to the construction of the present harbour including Victoria Dock and the South Breakwater, and the extension of the North Pier.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Gas street lighting arrived in 1824 and an enhanced water supply appeared in 1830 when water was pumped from the Dee to a reservoir in Union Place.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] An underground sewer system replaced open sewers in 1865.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city absorbed the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee in 1891.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Over the course of World War II Aberdeen was attacked 32 times by the German Luftwaffe.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] One of the most devastating attacks was on Wednesday 21 April 1943 when 29 Luftwaffe Dornier 217s flying from Stavanger, Norway attacked the city between the hours of 22:17 and 23:04.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A total of 98 civilians and 27 servicemen were killed, along with 12,000 houses damaged, after a mixture of 127 Incendiary, High Explosive and Cluster bombs were dropped on the city in one night.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Two books written in 2018 and 2022 using bombing records held in London identified that unexploded bombs from the 1943 raid were found in the 1950s and 1980s making the bombs dropped 129 in total.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Damage from the raid can still be seen in some parts of Aberdeen.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The arms and banner of the city show three silver towers on red.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This motif dates from at least the time of Robert the Bruce and represents the buildings that stood on the three hills of medieval Aberdeen: Aberdeen Castle on Castle Hill (today's Castlegate); the city gate on Port Hill; and a church on St Catherine's Hill (now levelled).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] "Bon Accord" is the motto of the city and is French for "Good Agreement".
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Legend tells that its use dates from a password used by Robert the Bruce during the 14th century Wars of Scottish Independence, when he and his men laid siege to the English-held Aberdeen Castle before destroying it in 1308.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It is still widely present in the city, throughout street names, business names and the city's Bon Accord shopping mall.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The shield in the coat of arms is supported by two leopards.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A local magazine is called the "Leopard" and, when Union Bridge was widened in the 20th century, small statues of the creature in a sitting position were cast and placed on top of the railing posts (known locally as Kelly's Cats).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city's toast is "Happy to meet, sorry to part, happy to meet again".
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2012, HSBC named Aberdeen as a leading business hub and one of eight 'super cities' spearheading the UK's economy, marking it as the only city in Scotland so designated.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2018, Aberdeen was found to be the best city in the UK to start a business in a study released by card payment firm Paymentsense.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen City is one of 32 council areas of Scotland, administered by Aberdeen City Council.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The council meets at Aberdeen Town House and has its main offices in the adjoining Marischal College.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The civic head and chair of the council is the Lord Provost.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The council area is also divided into 30 community council areas, 29 of which had community councils operating as at August 2024.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The first burgh of Aberdeen, covering just the New Aberdeen area near the mouth of the Dee, was created by David I (reigned 1124–1153).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Neighbouring Old Aberdeen to the north was subsequently made a separate burgh in 1489.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The burgh of Aberdeen was governed by a corporation, also known as the town council.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] As Aberdeen grew, the council's powers were inadequate to cater for the needs of the growing urban area.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A separate police commission was established in 1795 with powers to levy taxes and provide infrastructure ('police' in this context being its older meaning of civic government rather than law enforcement).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The first police commission was short-lived, but it was resurrected in 1818 after the town council went bankrupt in 1817.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] From 1818 until 1871 there was a dual system of local government, with the town council and police commission having different roles in Aberdeen's administration.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The police commission was eventually abolished in 1871 and its functions absorbed by the town council.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1891 the city boundaries were significantly enlarged, absorbing the neighbouring burghs of Old Aberdeen and Woodside, plus the Torry area on the south bank of the Dee.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The act of parliament which expanded the burgh also confirmed that Aberdeen was entitled to be called a city; it had commonly been described as a city prior to that, but (like most Scottish cities) without official recognition.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Following the absorption of Torry in 1891, the city boundaries straddled the counties of Aberdeenshire and Kincardineshire.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was made a county of itself in 1899.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1975 the burgh was replaced by the larger City of Aberdeen district within the Grampian region.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Further local government reforms in 1996 replaced the districts and regions created in 1975 with council areas; the pre-1996 City of Aberdeen district became the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the Scottish Parliament, the city is represented by three constituencies with different boundaries: Aberdeen Central and Aberdeen Donside are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Deeside and North Kincardine includes the North Kincardine ward of Aberdeenshire Council.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A further seven MSPs are elected as part of the North East Scotland electoral region.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the European Parliament the city was represented by six MEPs as part of the all-inclusive Scotland constituency.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is represented in the Parliament of the United Kingdom by two constituencies, Aberdeen North and Aberdeen South, which are wholly within the Aberdeen City council area.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Being situated between two river mouths, the city has little natural exposure of bedrock.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The small amount of geophysics done, and occasional building-related exposures, combined with small exposures in the banks of the River Don, suggest that it is actually sited on an inlier of Devonian "Old Red" sandstones and silts.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city extends to 186 km2 (72 sq mi), and includes the former burghs of Old Aberdeen, New Aberdeen, Woodside and the Torry area to the south of River Dee.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2024, this gave the city a population density of 1,249 inhabitants per square kilometre (3,230/sq mi).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city is built on many hills, with the original beginnings of the city growing from Castle Hill, St.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] When compared to mainland Europe, Aberdeen is further north than almost all of Denmark and plenty of southern Sweden, being just south of Gothenburg in terms of latitude.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen features an oceanic climate (Köppen *Cfb*), with far milder winter temperatures than one might expect for its northern location.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] However, statistically speaking, it is still the coldest city in the UK.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During the winter, especially throughout December, the length of the day is very short, averaging 6 hours and 41 minutes between sunrise and sunset at the winter solstice.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] As winter progresses, the length of the day grows fairly quickly, to 8 hours and 20 minutes by the end of January.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Around summer solstice, the days will be around 18 hours long, having 17 hours and 55 minutes between sunrise and sunset.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] During this time of the year marginal nautical twilight lasts the entire night.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Temperatures at this time of year hover around 17.0 °C (62.6 °F) during the day in most of the urban area, though nearer 16.0 °C (60.8 °F) directly on the coast, and around 18.0 to 19.0 °C (64.4 to 66.2 °F) in the westernmost suburbs.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Two weather stations collect climate data for the area, Aberdeen/Dyce Airport, and Craibstone.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Both are about 4+1⁄2 miles (7 km) to the northwest of the city centre, and given that they are in close proximity to each other, exhibit very similar climatic regimes.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Dyce tends to have marginally warmer daytime temperatures year-round owing to its slightly lower elevation, though it is more susceptible to harsh frosts.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The coldest temperature to occur in recent years was −16.8 °C (1.8 °F) during December 2010, while the following winter, Dyce set a new February high-temperature station record on 28 February 2012 of 17.2 °C (63.0 °F), and a new March high temperature record of 21.6 °C (70.9 °F) on 25 March 2012.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The average temperature of the sea ranges from 6.6 °C (43.9 °F) in March to 13.8 °C (56.8 °F) in August.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen locality population estimate is 198,590 (2020).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] For the wider settlement of Aberdeen including Cove Bay and Dyce, the population estimate is 220,690 (2020).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] For Aberdeen City council area, the population estimate is 231,780 (2024).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1396, the population was about 3,000.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The 2011 census showed fewer young people in Aberdeen, with 16.4% under 16, as opposed to the national average of 19.2%.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] According to the 2011 census Aberdeen is 91.9% white, ethnically, 24.7% were born outside Scotland, higher than the national average of 16%.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Of this population, 7.6% were born in other parts of the UK.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] 8.2% of Aberdonians stated to be from an ethnic minority (non-white) in the 2011 census, with 9,519 (4.3%) being Asian, with 3,385 (1.5%) coming from India and 2,187 (1.0%) being Chinese.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city has around 5,610 (2.6%) residents of African or Caribbean origin, which is a higher percentage than both Glasgow and Edinburgh.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the household, there were 97,013 individual dwellings recorded in the city, of which 61% were privately owned, 9% privately rented and 23% rented from the council.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The most popular type of dwellings are apartments which comprise 49% of residences followed by semi-detached at just below 22%.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The median income of a household in the city is £16,813 (the mean income is £20,292) (2005) which places approximately 18% households in the city below the poverty line (defined as 60% of the mean income).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Conversely, an Aberdeen postcode has the second highest number of millionaires of any postcode in the UK.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The proportion of people residing in Aberdeen born outside the UK was 21.1% in 2022, compared with 15.9% in 2011 and 6.3% in 2001.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Below are the fifteen largest overseas-born groups in Aberdeen according to the 2022 census, alongside the two previous censuses.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Christianity is the main religion practised in the city.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's largest denominations are the Church of Scotland (through the Presbytery of Aberdeen) and the Roman Catholic Church, both with numerous churches across the city, with the Scottish Episcopal Church having the third-largest number.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The census in 2022 showed that Aberdeen has the highest proportion of non-religious residents of any city in Scotland, with 58% of citizens claiming to have no religion.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In the Middle Ages, the Kirk of St Nicholas was the only burgh kirk and one of Scotland's largest parish churches.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Like a number of other Scottish kirks, it was subdivided after the Reformation, in this case into the East and West churches.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] At that time, the city also was home to houses of the Carmelites (Whitefriars) and Franciscans (Greyfriars).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The latter survives in modified form as the chapel of Marischal College.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] St Machar's Cathedral was built twenty years after David I (1124–1153) transferred the pre-Reformation diocese from Mortlach in Banffshire to Old Aberdeen in 1137.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Except the episcopate of William Elphinstone (1484–1511), building progressed slowly.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Gavin Dunbar, who followed him in 1518, completed the structure by adding the two western spires and the southern transept.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It is now a congregation of the Church of Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Mary's Cathedral is a Roman Catholic cathedral in Gothic style, erected in 1859.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Andrew's Cathedral serves the Scottish Episcopal Church.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It was constructed in 1817 as Archibald Simpson's first commission and contains a memorial to the consecration of the first bishop of the Episcopal Church in the United States of America, which took place nearby.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1804, St Peter's Church, the first permanent Roman Catholic church in the city after the Reformation was built.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Numerous other Protestant denominations have a presence in Aberdeen.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Salvation Army citadel on the Castlegate dominates the view of the east end of Union Street.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there is a Unitarian church, established in 1833 and located in Skene Terrace.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Christadelphians have been present in Aberdeen since at least 1844.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Over the years, they have rented space to meet at a number of locations and currently meet in the Inchgarth Community Centre in Garthdee.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Quaker meetinghouse on Crown Street, the only purpose built Friends meeting house in Scotland that is still in use today.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In addition, there are a number of Baptist congregations in the city, and Evangelical congregations have been appearing in significant numbers since the late 2000s.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city also has two meeting houses of the Church of Jesus Christ of Latter-day Saints (LDS Church).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are also four mosques in Aberdeen which serve the Islamic community in the city.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There is an Orthodox Jewish Synagogue established in 1945.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There is also a Thai Buddhist temple located in the Hazelhead area of the city.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are no formal Hindu buildings, although there is a fortnightly Hindu religious gathering on the first and third Sunday afternoons at Queens Cross Parish church hall.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen has a small Baháʼí society.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,756 residents aged three and over, 76,650 (35.2%) considered themselves able to speak or read the Scots language.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The 2022 Scottish Census reported that out of 217,760 residents aged three and over, 2,919 (1.3%) considered themselves able to speak or read Gaelic.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Traditionally, Aberdeen was home to fishing, textile mills, shipbuilding and paper-making.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] These industries have been largely replaced.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] High technology developments in the electronics design and development industry, research in agriculture and fishing and the oil industry, which have been largely responsible for Aberdeen's economic growth, are now major parts of Aberdeen's economy.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Until the 1970s, most of Aberdeen's leading industries dated from the 18th century; mainly these were textiles, foundry work, shipbuilding and paper-making, the oldest industry in the city, with paper having been first made there in 1694.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Paper-making has reduced in importance since the closures of Donside Paper Mill in 2001 and the Davidson Mill in 2005 leaving the Stoneywood Paper Mill with a workforce of approximately 500.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Textile production ended in 2004 when Richards of Aberdeen closed.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Grey granite was quarried at Rubislaw quarry for more than 300 years, and used for paving setts, kerb and building stones, and monumental and other ornamental pieces.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen granite was used to build the terraces of the Houses of Parliament and Waterloo Bridge in London.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The current owners have begun pumping 40 years of rainwater from the quarry to develop a heritage centre on the site.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In-shore fishing was once the predominant industry but was surpassed by deep-sea fisheries, which derived a great impetus from improved technologies throughout the 20th century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Catches have fallen because of overfishing and the use of the harbour by oil support vessels, and so although still an important fishing port it is now eclipsed by the more northerly ports of Peterhead and Fraserburgh.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Fisheries Research Services are headquartered in Aberdeen, and there is a marine research laboratory there.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is well regarded for the agricultural and soil research carried out at The James Hutton Institute (formerly the Macaulay Land Use Research Institute), which has close links to the city's two universities.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Rowett Research Institute is a world-renowned research centre for studies into food and nutrition located in Aberdeen.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It has produced three Nobel laureates and there is a high concentration of life scientists working in the city.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] As oil reserves in the North Sea decrease, there is an effort to rebrand Aberdeen as the **energy capital of Europe** rather than the oil capital, and there is interest in the development of new energy sources, and technology transfer from oil into renewable energy and other industries is underway.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The "Energetica" initiative led by Scottish Enterprise has been designed to accelerate this process.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has become a major world centre for undersea petroleum technology.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen had been a major maritime centre throughout the 19th century, when a group of local entrepreneurs launched the first steam-powered trawler.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The steam trawling industry expanded and by 1933 Aberdeen was Scotland's top fishing port, employing nearly 3,000 men with 300 vessels sailing from its harbour.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] By the time oil was coming on stream, much of the trawling fleet had relocated to Peterhead.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Geologists had speculated about oil and gas in the North Sea since the middle of the 20th century, but tapping its deep and inhospitable waters was another story.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] With the Middle Eastern oil sheiks becoming more aware of the political and economic power of their oil reserves and government threats of rationing, the industry began to consider the North Sea as a viable source of oil.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Exploration commenced in the 1960s and the first major find in the British sector was in November 1970 in the Forties field, 110 miles (180 km) east of Aberdeen.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] By late 1975, after years of intense construction, the necessary infrastructure was in place.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Oil flowed through the Forties pipeline system directly to the refinery at far-away Grangemouth.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2011, the Centre for Cities named Aberdeen as the best-placed city for growth in Britain, as the country looked to emerge from the recent economic downturn.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] With energy still providing the backbone of the local economy, recent years have seen very large new investment in the North Sea owing to rising oil prices and favourable government tax incentives.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This has led to several oil majors and independents building new global offices in the city.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Five of Scotland's top ten businesses are based in Aberdeen with a collective turnover of £14 billion, yielding a profit in excess of £2.4 billion.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Alongside this 29 of Scotland's top 100 businesses are located in Aberdeen with an employment rate of 77.9%, making it the second highest UK city for employment.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Figures released in 2016 ranked Aberdeen as having the second highest number of patents processed per person in the UK.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The traditional shopping streets are Union Street and George Street, now complemented by shopping centres, including the Bon Accord Centre and the Trinity Shopping Centre.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A £190 million retail development, Union Square, reached completion in late September/early October 2009.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Major retail parks away from the city centre include the Berryden Retail Park, the Kittybrewster Retail Park and the Beach Boulevard Retail Park.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Market has been rebuilt twice, but closed in 2020.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In March 2004, Aberdeen was awarded Fairtrade City status by the Fairtrade Foundation.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen's architecture is known for its principal use during the Victorian era of granite, which has led to its local nickname of the Granite City.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In Castle Street, a continuation eastwards of Union Street, is the new Aberdeen Town House, a very prominent landmark in Aberdeen, built between 1868 and 1873 to a design by Peddie and Kinnear.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Alexander Marshall Mackenzie's extension to Marischal College on Broad Street, opened by King Edward VII in 1906, created the second largest granite building in the world (after the Escorial, Madrid).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has long been famous for its 45 parks and gardens, and citywide floral displays which include two million roses, eleven million daffodils and three million crocuses.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city has won the Royal Horticultural Society's Britain in Bloom 'Best City' award ten times, the overall Scotland in Bloom competition twenty times and the large city category every year since 1968.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] However, despite recent spurious reports, Aberdeen has never been banned from the Britain in Bloom competition.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The city won the 2006 Scotland in Bloom "Best City" award along with the International Cities in Bloom award.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The suburb of Dyce also won the Small Towns award.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Duthie Park opened in 1883 on the north bank of the River Dee.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It was named after and given to the city by Miss Elizabeth Crombie Duthie of Ruthrieston in 1881.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Hazlehead Park, is large and forested, and located on the outskirts of the city.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Johnston Gardens is a small park of one hectare in the west end of the city.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 2002, the garden was named the best garden in the British Islands.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Seaton Park, formerly the grounds of a private house, is on the edge of the grounds of St Machar's Cathedral and was acquired for the city in 1947.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has hosted several theatres throughout its history, some of which have been converted or destroyed.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Today, all railway services to the south run via Dundee.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The faster main line from Aberdeen to Perth via Forfar and Strathmore closed in 1967, as a result of the Beeching cuts; the faster main line from Perth to Edinburgh via Glenfarg also closed subsequently in 1970.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] A second station, at Dyce, serves the north of the city centre; it is on the Aberdeen–Inverness line.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] First Aberdeen operates the majority of city bus services, as the successor to Grampian Regional Transport (GRT) and Aberdeen Corporation Tramways.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Secondary operators include Stagecoach Bluebird and Stagecoach South Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is the global headquarters of parent company FirstGroup, having grown from the GRT Group.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] First is still based at the former Aberdeen Tramways depot on King Street, which has now been redeveloped into a new headquarters and bus depot.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] On 18 April 2025, the "Aberdeen Adventurer" tour bus scheme ran by McGill's Bus Services was launched with 10 stops around the city on a 75-minute loop.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Stops include King's College, Pittodrie Stadium and the Aberdeen Art Gallery with the service due to end on 20 September 2026.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen International Airport (ABZ), sited in Dyce in the north of the city, serves domestic and international destinations in France, the Netherlands, Spain, Ireland and Scandinavian countries.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The heliport, which serves the oil industry and rescue services, is one of the world's busiest commercial heliports.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is connected to the UK's National Cycle Network; it has a track to the south, connecting to cities including Dundee and Edinburgh, and one to the north that forks about 10 miles (15 km) from the city into two different tracks heading to Inverness and Fraserburgh respectively.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Two popular shared-use paths, along old railway lines, are the Deeside Way to Banchory (which will eventually connect to Ballater) and the Formartine and Buchan Way to Ellon, both used by a mixture of cyclists, walkers and occasionally horses.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In May 2026, a self-service e-bike hire scheme was introduced in Aberdeen, operated by Voi Technology.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Some 350 bikes are available on a pay-as-you-go basis.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The scheme replaced an earlier bike hire scheme which was operated between 2022 and 2024 by *The Big Issue* and Sharebike but which was scrapped because of funding issues as well as vandalism.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen Harbour is important as the largest in the north of Scotland and serves the ferry route to Orkney and Shetland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Established in 1136, the harbour has been referred to as the "oldest business in Britain".
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Dee Estuary, Aberdeen's harbour, started out as a fishing port, moving on to steam trawlers and serving the oil industry; it is now a major port of departure for the Baltic and Scandinavia.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has two universities, the ancient University of Aberdeen, and Robert Gordon University, a modern university often referred to as RGU.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen has a high proportion of students of 11.5%, higher than the national average of 7%.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The University of Aberdeen began as King's College, Aberdeen, which was founded in 1495 by William Elphinstone (1431–1514), Bishop of Aberdeen and Chancellor of Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Marischal College, a separate institution, was founded in New Aberdeen by George Keith, fifth Earl Marischal of Scotland in 1593.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] These institutions were merged by the Universities (Scotland) Act 1858 to form the University of Aberdeen.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The university is the fifth oldest in the English-speaking world and offers degrees in a full range of disciplines.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Its main campus is in Old Aberdeen in the north of the city and it currently has approximately 14,000 students.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The university's debating society is the oldest in Scotland, founded in 1848 as the King's College Debating Society.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Today, Aberdeen is consistently ranked among the top 200 universities in the world and is ranked within the top 20 universities in the United Kingdom.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen was also named the 2019 Scottish University of the Year by The Times and Sunday Times Good University Guide.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In early 2022, Aberdeen opened the Science Teaching Hub.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Robert Gordon's College (originally Robert Gordon's Hospital) was founded in 1750 by the merchant Robert Gordon, grandson of the map maker Robert Gordon of Straloch, and was further endowed in 1816 by Alexander Simpson of Collyhill.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Originally devoted to the instruction and maintenance of the sons of poor burgesses of guild and trade in the city, it was reorganised in 1881 as a day and night school for secondary and technical education.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1903, the vocational education component of the college was designated a Central Institution and was renamed as the Robert Gordon Institute of Technology in 1965.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] In 1992, university status was awarded and it became Robert Gordon University.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The university has expanded and developed significantly in recent years, and was named Best Modern University in the UK for 2012 by *The Sunday Times*.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] It was previously *The Sunday Times* Scottish University of the Year for 2011, primarily because of its record on graduate employment.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Aberdeen is also home to two artistic schools: Gray's School of Art, founded in 1886, which is one of the oldest established colleges of art in the UK.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Scott Sutherland School of Architecture and Built Environment, was one of the first architectural schools to have its training courses recognised by the Royal Institute of British Architects.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Both are now part of Robert Gordon University and are based at its Garthdee campus.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] North East Scotland College has several campuses in the city and offers a wide variety of part-time and full-time courses leading to several different qualifications in science.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Scottish Agricultural College is based just outside Aberdeen, on the Craibstone Estate.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] This is situated beside the roundabout for Aberdeen Airport on the A96.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The college provides three services—Learning, Research and Consultancy.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The college features many land-based courses such as Agriculture, Countryside Management, Sustainable Environmental Management and Rural Business Management.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are a variety of courses from diplomas to master's degrees.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Marine Laboratory Aberdeen, which specialises in fisheries, Macaulay Land Use Research Institute (soil science), and the Rowett Research Institute (animal nutrition) are some other higher education institutions.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] The Aberdeen College of Performing Arts also provides full-time Drama and Musical Theatre training at Further Education level.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are currently 15 secondary schools and 54 primary schools which are run by the city council.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] There are a number of private schools in Aberdeen: Robert Gordon's College, Albyn School, St Margaret's School for Girls, the International School of Aberdeen and a Waldorf/Steiner School.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] State secondary schools in Aberdeen include Aberdeen Grammar School, Bridge of Don Academy, Bucksburn Academy, Cults Academy, Dyce Academy, Harlaw Academy, Hazlehead Academy, Lochside Academy, Northfield Academy, Oldmachar Academy and St Machar Academy.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p01] Independent primary and secondary schools in Aberdeen include Albyn School, Robert Gordon's College, St Margaret's School for Girls, and the International School of Aberdeen.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city has a wide range of cultural activities, amenities, and museums, and is regularly visited by Scotland's National Arts Companies.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It was awarded the Nicholson Trophy for the best-kept town at the Britain in Bloom contest in 1975.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery houses a collection of Impressionist, Victorian, Scottish and 20th-century British paintings as well as collections of silver and glass.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It also includes The Alexander Macdonald Bequest, a collection of late 19th-century works donated by the museum's first benefactor and a constantly changing collection of contemporary work and regular visiting exhibitions.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Art Gallery reopened in 2019 after a four-year refurbishment costing £34.6m.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Maritime Museum, located in Shiprow, tells the story of Aberdeen's links with the sea from the days of sail and clipper ships to the latest oil and gas exploration technology.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It includes an 8.5-metre-high (28 ft) model of the Murchison oil production platform and a 19th-century assembly taken from Rattray Head lighthouse Provost Ross' House is the second oldest dwelling house in the city.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It was built in 1593 and became the residence of Provost John Ross of Arnage in 1702.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The house retains some original medieval features, including a kitchen, fireplaces and beam-and-board ceilings.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Gordon Highlanders Museum tells the story of one of Scotland's best known regiments.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Provost Skene's House on Flourmill Lane dates from 1545 and is the oldest surviving townhouse in the city.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It reopened in October 2021 after significant refurbishment costing £3.8m.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] One of the new exhibitions is a Hall of Heroes featuring 100 Aberdonians who have made a significant contribution to the city.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Tollbooth Museum on the Castlegate (currently closed to visitors) is a former jail, which first opened as a public museum in 1995.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Treasure Hub is a storage facility for Aberdeen Museums and Galleries containing over 100,000 items.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The store is open for infrequent tours, for example as part of Doors Open Day.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Marischal Museum holds the principal collections of the University of Aberdeen, comprising some 80,000 items in the areas of fine art, Scottish history and archaeology, and European, Mediterranean and Near Eastern archaeology.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The permanent displays and reference collections are augmented by regular temporary exhibitions, and since its closure to the public it now has a virtual online presence It closed to the public in 2008.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The King's Museum acts as the main museum of the university now.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Student Show, performed annually without interruption since 1921, under the auspices of the Aberdeen Students' Charities Campaign, is the longest-running of its kind in the United Kingdom.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It is written, produced and performed by students and graduates of Aberdeen's universities and higher education institutions.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Since 1929—other than on a handful of occasions—it has been staged at His Majesty's Theatre.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] National festivals which visited Aberdeen in 2012 included the British Science Festival in September, hosted by the University of Aberdeen but with events also taking place at Robert Gordon University and at other venues across the city.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In February 2012 the University of Aberdeen also hosted the Inter Varsity Folk Dance Festival, the longest-running folk festival in the United Kingdom.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Spectra, an annual light festival hosted in different locations across the city.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Nuart, a festival showcasing street art around the city.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2020, the WayWORD Festival was launched by the University of Aberdeen WORD centre for creative writing.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] This yearly programme celebrates the arts through readings, performances, workshops and discussion panels.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There have been many notable headliners including Val McDermid, Irvine Welsh and Douglas Stuart (writer).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Galas are held annually throughout the city, the most notable being the Culter Gala, which is usually held on the last Saturday of May.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The local dialect of Lowland Scots is often known as Doric and is spoken not just in the city, but across the northeast of Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] It differs somewhat from other Scots dialects: most noticeable are the pronunciation "f" for what is normally written "wh" and "ee" for what in standard English would usually be written "oo" (Scots "ui").
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Every year the annual Doric Festival takes place in Aberdeenshire to celebrate the history of the north-east's language.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen is home to Scotland's oldest newspaper the *Press and Journal*, a local and regional newspaper first published in 1747.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The *Press and Journal* and its sister paper the tabloid *Evening Express* are printed six days a week by Aberdeen Journals.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There was one free newspaper, the *Aberdeen Citizen*.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] BBC Scotland has a network studio production base in the city's Beechgrove area, and BBC Aberdeen produces *The Beechgrove Potting Shed* for radio while Tern Television produces *The Beechgrove Garden*.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city is also home to STV North (formerly Grampian Television), which produces the regional news programmes such as *STV News at Six*, as well as local commercials.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The station, based at Craigshaw Business Park in Tullos, was based at larger studios in Queens Cross from September 1961 until June 2003.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Music venues include the Music Hall and the P&J Live.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen region has given its name to a number of dishes, including the Aberdeen buttery (also known as "rowie") and Aberdeen Sausage.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2015, a study was published in The Scotsman which analysed the presence of branded fast food outlets in Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Of the ten towns and cities analysed, Aberdeen was found to have the lowest per capita concentration, with just 0.12 stores per 1,000 inhabitants.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The public health service in Scotland, NHS Scotland provides for the people of Aberdeen through the NHS Grampian health board.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Albyn Hospital is a private hospital located in the west end of the city.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen City Council is responsible for city-owned infrastructure which is paid for by a mixture of Council Tax and income from the Scottish Government.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure and services run by the council include: nursery, primary and secondary education, roads, clearing snow in winter, city wardens, maintaining parks, refuse collection, economic development, public analyst, public mortuary, street cleaning and street lighting.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Infrastructure in private hands includes electricity, gas and telecoms.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Water and sewerage services are provided by Scottish Water.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The first ever recorded game of football, was outlined by teacher David Wedderburn in his book "Vocabula" written in 1633, during his time teaching at Aberdeen Grammar School.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There is one Aberdeen-based football club in the SPFL.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] (The Dons) play in the Scottish Premiership at Pittodrie Stadium.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club won the European Cup Winners Cup and the European Super Cup in 1983, the Scottish Premier League Championship four times (1955, 1980, 1984 and 1985), and the Scottish Cup eight times (1947, 1970, 1982, 1983, 1984, 1986, 1990 and 2025).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of Alex Ferguson, Aberdeen was a major force in British football during the 1980s.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Under the management of McInnes the team won the 2014 Scottish League Cup and followed it up with a second-place league finish for the first time in more than 20 years in the following season.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] But it was over the last few seasons that results stagnated and McInnes was replaced by former Aberdeen and Newcastle player Stephen Glass.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Cove Rangers, as of season 2024-25 play in League One, at the Balmoral Stadium in the suburb of Cove Bay.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Cove won the Highland Football League championship in 2001, 2008, 2009, 2013 and 2019, winning the League Two play-offs in 2019 and earning promotion.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] At the point at which the 2019/20 League Two season was curtailed due to the COVID-19 pandemic, Cove were sitting top of the League Two table and were promoted as Champions.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Other local teams include Banks o'Dee who play at Spain Park in the Highland Football League and members of the SJFA North Region; Culter, Dyce, Stoneywood Parkvale, Glentanar, Sunnybank Hall Russell United, Bridge of Don Thistle and Hermes.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen hosted Caledonia Reds, a Scottish rugby team, before they merged with the Glasgow Warriors in 1998.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2005 the President of the SRU said it was hoped eventually to establish a professional team in Aberdeen.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In November 2008 the city hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Canada, with Scotland winning 41–0.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In November 2010 the city once again hosted a rugby international at Pittodrie between Scotland and Samoa, with Scotland winning 19–16.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Warriors rugby league team play in the Rugby League Conference Division One.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Warriors also run Under 15's and 17's teams.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Grammar School won the Saltire Schools Cup in 2011.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Royal Aberdeen Golf Club, founded in 1780 is the sixth oldest golf club in the world, and hosted the Senior British Open in 2005, and the amateur team event the Walker Cup in 2011.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Royal Aberdeen also hosted the Scottish Open in 2014, won by Justin Rose.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club has a second course, and there are public golf courses at Auchmill, Balnagask, Hazlehead and King's Links.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There are new courses planned for the area, including world-class facilities with major financial backing, the city and shire are set to become important in golf tourism.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In Summer 2012, Donald Trump opened a new state of the art golf course at Menie, just north of the city, as the Trump International Golf Links, Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Ice hockey in Aberdeen boasts a history that began in the early 20th century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Glaciarium on Forbesfield Road became a hub for games, featuring teams like the Grammar School Former Pupils and the Aberdeen Ice Hockey Club.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] However, the sport all but died out with the onset of WW1.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The sport was revived in the city with the opening of the Linx Ice Arena in 1992.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Lynx plays in the Scottish National League and is based at the Linx Ice Arena.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Founded in 2005, they won back to back regular season titles in 2022-23 and 2023–24 and won the play-off championship in 2015-16 and again in 2024–25.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] They regularly sell out home games and are the second best supported sports team in the city after Aberdeen FC.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The City of Aberdeen Swim Team (COAST) was based in Northfield swimming pool, but since the opening of the Aberdeen Aquatics Centre in 2014, it is now based there, as it has a 50 m pool as opposed to the 25 m pool at Northfield.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The team comprises several smaller swimming clubs and has enjoyed success throughout Scotland and in international competitions.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Three of the team's swimmers qualified for the 2006 Commonwealth Games.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There are four boat clubs that row on the River Dee: Aberdeen Boat Club (ABC), Aberdeen Schools Rowing Association (ASRA), Aberdeen University Boat Club (AUBC) and Robert Gordon University Boat Club (RGUBC).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city has one national league side, Stoneywood-Dyce.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Local "Grades" cricket has been played in Aberdeen since 1884.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeenshire were the 2009 and 2014 Scottish National Premier League and Scottish Cup Champions.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen University Shinty Club (Scottish Gaelic: Club Camanachd Oilthigh Obar Dheathain) is the oldest constituted shinty club in the world, dating back to 1861.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The city council operates public tennis courts in various parks including an indoor tennis centre at Westburn Park.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Beach Leisure Centre is home to a climbing wall, gymnasium and a swimming pool.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] There are numerous swimming pools dotted around the city notably the largest, the Bon Accord Baths which closed down in 2008.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In common with many other major towns and cities in the UK, Aberdeen has an active roller derby league, Granite City Roller Derby.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Aberdeen Roughnecks American football club is a new team that started in 2012 and is the first team that Aberdeen has witnessed since the Granite City Oilers that began in 1986 and were wound up in the mid-1990s.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Aberdeen Oilers Floorball Club was founded in 2007.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club initially attracted a range of experienced Scandinavian and other European players who were studying in Aberdeen.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Since their formation, Aberdeen Oilers have played in the British Floorball Northern League and went on to win the league in the 2008/09 season.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The club played a major role in setting up a ladies league in Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The Oilers' ladies team ended up second in the first ladies league season (2008/09).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] One of the earliest known disasters is the Storegga Slide in the mesolithic period in 6225–6170 BCE which caused tsunami waves to hit North sea coastal areas, with wave heights of 3-6 meters in the north east Scotland areas.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1876, the River Dee ferryboat disaster took place when 32 people drowned in the mouth of the River Dee.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The 20th century includes a World War II disaster when in 1943, a Luftwaffe raid dropped 129 bombs on Aberdeen resulting in 125 deaths..
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1964, a typhoid outbreak occurred with 400 cases and three fatalities.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1983, the Aberdeen taxi driver George Murdoch was killed, the murder case is unsolved.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In modern time, accidents have been related with offshore drilling.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1988, the oil platform Piper Alpha, located 190 km north-east of Aberdeen, exploded and collapsed, killing 165.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The accident is the worst ever offshore oil and gas disaster in terms of lives lost.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Hazlehead Park contains a memorial to the crew. .
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 1995, Bristow Helicopters Flight 56C was struck by lightning and emergency landed in the sea.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] The 18 crew and passengers on board survived.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] In 2009, the Bond Offshore Helicopters Flight 85N crashed 20 km north-east of Peterhead, while returning from an oil platform to Aberdeen Airport.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/aberdeen-p02] Johnston Gardens contains a memorial to the deceased.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] He was born in Edinburgh in 1707, the son of Rev James Webster, second charge of Tolbooth parish in St Giles Cathedral and a covenanting minister, originally from Fife.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] Alexander was educated at the High School of Edinburgh then studied at Edinburgh University.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] He was licensed to preach by the Presbytery of Haddington in March 1733.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] In September 1733 Alexander was ordained as minister of the Church of Scotland at Culross Parish Church in western Fife.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] On 2 June 1737 he was translated to Tolbooth parish, one of the four parishes contained in St Giles Cathedral in Edinburgh.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] He propounded a scheme in 1742 for providing pensions for the widows of ministers.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] The tables which he drew up from information obtained from all the presbyteries of Scotland were based on a system of actuarial calculation that supplied a precedent followed by insurance companies in modern times for reckoning averages of longevity.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] Webster published in 1748 his *Calculations*, setting forth the principles on which his scheme for widows' pensions was based; he also wrote a defence of the Methodist movement in 1742, and *Zeal for the Civil and Religious Interests of Mankind Commended* (1754).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] In 1755, the government commissioned Webster to obtain data for the first census of Scotland, which he carried out in the same year.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] In 1753, he was elected Moderator of the General Assembly of the Church of Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] In 1771, he was appointed a Dean of the Chapel Royal and Chaplain in Ordinary to George III in Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] In 1775, he is listed as living on Castlehill, at the top of the Royal Mile.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] Socially, despite his 'High Flying' Evangelical position in the Kirk, he was a convivial man, known as *Bonum Magnum* for his capacity for claret.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] His wife's nephew Boswell often mentions dining with the family.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] He died in Edinburgh on 25 January 1784 and is buried beside Mary in Greyfriars Kirkyard, Edinburgh, in a now-unmarked grave.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] In June 1737 he was married to Mary Erskine (d.1766), daughter of Col.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] Mary's sister Euphemia Erskine, was the mother of James Boswell and Boswell visited the family on Castlehill with his friend Dr Johnson.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] A plaque on the building makes reference to Boswell but not to Webster.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/alexander-webster] And, kissing those lips, find you woman again.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] Biggar occupies a key location close to two of Scotland's great rivers, the Clyde flowing to the west, and the Tweed flowing to the east.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] Stone and Bronze-age artefacts have been found in the area but the strongest evidence of settlement occurs on the hills surrounding the town.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] One of these is Bizzyberry Hill where Iron Age remains dating back almost 2,000 years have been found.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] In the 12th century, in return for the promise of support, King David I gave the lands of Biggar to Baldwin, a Fleming leader.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] He built a motte and bailey castle, which can still be seen north-west of the High Street.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The first permanent crossing of the Biggar Burn was also built.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] It is thought that there has been a church at Biggar since the 6th or 7th century, although the first stone kirk was built in 1164, on the site of the existing kirk.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] In the 14th century, the Fleming family were given lands in the area by Robert the Bruce, whose cause they had supported.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The Flemings built Boghall Castle, visible as a ruin until the early 20th century, but now only represented by a few mounds.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The town continued to grow as an important market town, and in 1451 it became a burgh.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The market place remains the central focus of the town.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The kirk was rebuilt as a Collegiate church in 1546 for Malcolm, 3rd Lord Fleming, the last to be established before the Reformation of 1560.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The Flemings found themselves on the wrong side in the 16th century, when they supported Mary, Queen of Scots.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] Their lands remained in the Fleming family until the 18th century when the male line of succession ended.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The lands passed into the Elphinstone family in 1735 on the marriage of the heiress Lady Clementina Fleming to Charles, Lord Elphinstone.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] Biggar Gas Works opened in 1836, producing gas from coal.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] In 1973, with the introduction of natural gas, the works closed.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] Biggar had its own railway station on the Symington, Biggar and Broughton Railway between 1860 and 1953.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] In 1899 farmers, Thomas Blackwood Murray and Norman Fulton, located in Biggar founded Albion Motors as a small business which eventually grew into the largest truck company in the British Empire.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The company still exists as part of the Leyland DAF group.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The archives of Albion motors can still be found in Biggar.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] In the summer of 1940 several thousands of Polish soldiers were stationed here, having been evacuated after the collapse of France.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The singer Richard Tauber, whose wife Diana Napier was working with the Polish Red Cross, put on a special performance of the operetta The Land of Smiles during a two-week run in Glasgow.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] Later the Polish soldiers moved to the east coast of Scotland to defend the coast and to train for their deployment as the 1st Polish Armoured Division in Normandy, Belgium and the Netherlands.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The fictional Midculter, which features in Dorothy Dunnett's *Lymond Chronicles* novels, is set here.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The town was once served by the Symington, Biggar and Broughton Railway, which ran from the Caledonian Railway (now the West Coast Main Line) at Symington to join the Peebles Railway at Peebles.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The station and signal box are still standing but housing has been built on the line running west from the station and the railway running east from the station is a public footpath to Broughton, part of the Biggar Country Path network.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] This town has two schools, one primary, and one secondary.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The secondary school, Biggar High School, also admits pupils from surrounding small towns and villages.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] Biggar Primary is a small school, located on South Back Road, with a current roll of 238 pupils.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The High School, located on John's Loan and adjacent to the primary, shares its sports facilities with the primary school when the occasion demands it.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The annual primary Sports Day is held on the High School playing field.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] In 2007 local estate agent John Riley, encouraged a group of Biggar residents to launch the Carbon Neutral Biggar project, with the stated aim of becoming the first carbon neutral town in Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The launch of the project, covered in both local and national media, took place at the town's annual eco forum in May 2007.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The group has formed links with the town of Ashton Hayes in Cheshire, which has a similar group working toward carbon neutral status for the town.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The new Biggar & Upper Clydesdale Museum run by the Biggar Museum Trust opened in 2015 and the Biggar Gasworks Museum is the only preserved gas works in Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] Additionally, Biggar has Scotland's only permanent puppet theatre, Biggar Puppet Theatre, which is run by the Purves Puppets family.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] Biggar Corn Exchange, now also used as a theatre, was completed in 1861.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] Ian Hamilton Finlay's home and garden at Little Sparta is nearby in the Pentland Hills.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The town hosts an annual arts festival, the Biggar Little Festival.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The town has traditionally held a huge bonfire at Hogmanay.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The town has only one church congregation: Biggar Kirk (Church of Scotland) linked with Black Mount Church (located in Dolphinton).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] Biggar was the birthplace of Thomas Gladstones, the grandfather of William Ewart Gladstone.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] Hugh MacDiarmid spent his later years at Brownsbank, near the town.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] The town of Biggar is 200 metres (660 ft) above sea level.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] Biggar has an oceanic climate (Köppen: *Cfb*).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/biggar-south-lanarkshire] Camps Reservoir is a nearby weather station situated at an elevation of 295 m (968 ft).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The **Black Death** was a plague pandemic that occurred in Europe from 1346 to 1353.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] It was one of the most fatal pandemics in human history, leading to the death of up to 50 million people, or 50% of Europe's 14th-century population.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The disease is caused by the bacterium *Yersinia pestis* and is spread by fleas and through the air.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] One of the most significant events in European history, the Black Death had far-reaching population, economic, and cultural effects.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] It was the beginning of the second plague pandemic.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The plague created religious, social, and economic upheavals, with profound effects on the course of European history.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The Black Death was the second great natural disaster to strike Europe during the Late Middle Ages (the first one being the Great Famine of 1315–1317) and is estimated to have killed 30% to 60% of the European population, as well as approximately 33% of the population of the Middle East.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] There were further outbreaks throughout the Late Middle Ages and, also due to other contributing factors (the crisis of the late Middle Ages), the European population did not regain its 14th century level until the 16th century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] Outbreaks of the plague recurred around the world until the early 19th century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The origin of the Black Death is disputed.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] Genetic analysis suggests *Yersinia pestis* bacteria evolved approximately 7,000 years ago, at the beginning of the Neolithic, with flea-mediated strains emerging around 3,800 years ago during the late Bronze Age.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The immediate territorial origins of the Black Death and its outbreak remain unclear, with some evidence pointing towards Central Asia, China, the Middle East, and Europe.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The pandemic was reportedly first introduced to Europe during the siege of the Genoese trading port of Caffa in Crimea by the Golden Horde army of Jani Beg in 1347.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] From Crimea, it was most likely carried by fleas living on the black rats that travelled on Genoese ships, spreading through the Mediterranean Basin and reaching North Africa, West Asia, and the rest of Europe via Constantinople, Sicily, and the Italian Peninsula.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] There is evidence that once it came ashore, the Black Death mainly spread from person-to-person as pneumonic plague, thus explaining the quick inland spread of the epidemic, which was faster than would be expected if the primary vector was rat fleas causing bubonic plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] A 2026 study published in *Nature* identified the oldest known evidence of plague outbreaks in human remains, finding traces of Yersinia pestis DNA in the teeth of 18 ancient hunter-gatherers from four cemeteries near Lake Baikal in Siberia.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] Carbon dating revealed two outbreaks, with the earliest cases dating to approximately 5,500 years ago — some 200 years earlier than previously established.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] Researchers concluded the disease likely spread initially from marmots through contact with raw organs or infected hides, and also transmitted between people through respiratory means.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] Many victims were young children, with three young girls buried side by side among the dead.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] There has been a quest to find "patient zero", the earliest known victim(s) with evidence of the Black Death.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] In 2022, in an article called "*The source of the Black Death in fourteenth-century central Eurasia*", researchers pointed to the earliest victims of the plague found at two cemeteries in the Chüy Valley near Lake Issyk-Kul in modern Kyrgyzstan.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] Here graves had tombstones with Syriac inscription, providing the name of the deceased, year of death and often the cause of death, showing a spike due to "pestilence" in 1338–1339.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The article reported DNA data to provide genetic evidence from the teeth of seven individuals from the two cemeteries at Kara-Djigach and Burana finding evidence of *Yersinia pestis*.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] This confirms that the Yersinia pestis strain found in Kyrgyzstan predates and was the direct ancestor of the Black Death strains that devastated Europe and the Middle East starting in 1346–1347.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The Mongol Empire, founded by Genghis Khan, reached its peak expansion between 1206 and 1279.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] By the time the Black Death emerged in Central Asia in the late 1330s, the Mongol Empire had already reached its maximum geographic extent and had fractured into four distinct khanates (the Golden Horde, the Ilkhanate, the Chagatai Khanate, and the Yuan Dynasty).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The Black Death became a catalyst for the Mongol Empire's fall.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] It disrupted trade as the Mongols relied on trade along the Silk Road and the plague spread along these trade routes, killing the merchants and officials who maintained the network.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] There was a depopulation of the ruling elite, decimating the Mongol administrative class in the Ilkhanate (Persia) and the Golden Horde (Russia), leading to political instability and the eventual overthrow of Mongol rulers.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The Chagatai Khanate served as the "Ground Zero" for the genetic ancestor of the Black Death.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] A 2022 research paper by Spyrou et al. identified the Yersinia pestis strain in the cemetery sites of Kara-Djigach and Tolyak in 1338–1339, which were located within the borders of the Chagatai Khanate.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The discovery in this specific khanate changes the "origin story" of the Black Death from a vague Far Eastern source (China) to a specific Central Asian focal point.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The Chagatai Khanate sits at the very root of the "four-way split" (diversification) of the plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] This means the version that devastated the Ilkhanate, the Golden Horde, and Europe all radiated out from this single Central Asian source.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The Chagatai Khanate was the geographic heart of the Silk Road.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] It acted as the bridge between the Yuan Dynasty in the east and the Ilkhanate/Golden Horde in the west.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] Because the Mongols maintained high-speed postal stations (Yam) and protected merchant caravans, they unintentionally created the perfect laboratory for a localized rodent-borne disease to become a transcontinental pandemic.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The Golden Horde played a pivotal role in the transmission of the Black Death from Central Asia to the Mediterranean.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] In 1346, the plague reached the Horde's territories along the Volga River, devastating major urban centers like the capital Sarai.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The pandemic is famously associated with the Siege of Caffa (1346), where the Mongol army under Khan Jani Beg (r.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] 1342–1357) suffered heavy casualties from the disease while besieging the Genoese port.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] Chroniclers like Gabriele de' Mussi recorded that the Mongols catapulted plague-infected corpses into the city, an early instance of biological warfare, which likely contributed to the escape of infected Genoese ships toward Sicily and Europe.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The plague triggered a profound domestic collapse for the Golden Horde, with the mass death of the ruling elite and the administrative class leading to a period of protracted civil war known as the "Great Troubles" (*Zamyatna*), beginning in 1359.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] This internal fragmentation, combined with the loss of tax revenue from the depopulated Silk Road trade routes, weakened Mongol authority over its Russian vassals, eventually facilitating the rise of the Grand Duchy of Moscow.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The sudden collapse of the Ilkhanate following the death of its ruler Abu Sa'id in 1335 and turmoil that followed, have been linked to the outbreak of the Black Death.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The Tian Shan mountains in Kyrgyzstan was a major node on the trade routes leading directly into the Ilkhanate.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] It is biologically plausible that the plague was already hitting nomadic camps and trade hubs before it was recorded by urban chroniclers.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] However, no evidence of mass graves or direct evidence of the plague have been found in the Ilkhanate dating to the early 1330s CE.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] George Childs Kohn, in his *Encyclopedia of Plague and Pestilence*, he explicitly lists 1335 as a potential early date for the plague reaching the Ilkhanate, citing the sudden death of the Khan and his court as circumstantial evidence.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] John France, a military and medieval historian who argues that the "shattering" of the Mongol military machine in the 1330s suggests a massive loss of manpower that political infighting alone cannot explain.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] Peter Jackson, in The Mongols and the Islamic World, notes the suspicious timing.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] While he remains cautious, he highlights that the "administrative paralysis" following 1335 mirrors the later effects of the Black Death in Europe.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] McNeill, in his seminal work *Plagues and Peoples* (1976), pioneered the theory that the Mongol Empire's trade routes were the primary "caravanserai" for the plague, suggesting the Ilkhanate was the first major urban center to be hit.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] In 1368, the Fall of the Yuan Dynasty in China was due to the combination of plague, famine, and flooding that weakened Mongol authority, fueling the Red Turban Rebellion (c.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] 1351–1368) that established the Ming Dynasty.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] In India, the Tughlaq Dynasty ruled by Muhammad bin Tughlaq (r.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] 1325–1351) does not have records of the Black Death.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] There are records of outbreaks of massive pestilence (waba) around 1334–1335 (Warangal/Bidar Outbreak) and 1344.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] However, there is no clear evidence proving it was due to the Black Death bacterium.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] Ibn Battuta provides the primary description of this event at the time the army was stationed near Bidar/Warangal in the Deccan.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The Waba (Pestilence) was described as a disease that struck with such speed that soldiers would fall dead almost instantly.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] It was reported that nearly half of the royal army perished.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The Sultan himself became critically ill but survived, eventually retreating to Delhi to escape the contagion.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The description of the Indian outbreak is somewhat general, focusing more on the suddenness of death and the high fever rather than the distinct physical markers like buboes.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] This has led some researchers to suggest it may have been a different tropical disease, such as a severe form of malaria or cholera.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] European writers contemporary with the plague described the disease in Latin as *pestis* or *pestilentia*, 'pestilence'; *epidemia*, 'epidemic'; *mortalitas*, 'mortality'.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] In English prior to the 18th century, the event was called the "pestilence" or "great pestilence", "the plague" or the "great death".
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] Subsequent to the pandemic "the *furste moreyn*" (first murrain) or "first pestilence" was applied, to distinguish the mid-14th century phenomenon from other infectious diseases and epidemics of plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The 1347 pandemic plague was not referred to specifically as "black", at the time, in any European language.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The expression "black death" had occasionally been applied to other fatal or dangerous diseases.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] In English, "Black death" was not used to describe this plague pandemic, however, until the 1750s; the term is first attested in 1755, where it translated Danish: *den sorte død*, lit.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] Previously, most European languages had named the pandemic a variant or calque of the Latin: *magna mortalitas*, lit.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The phrase 'black death' – describing Death as black – is very old.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] Homer used it in the Odyssey to describe the monstrous Scylla, with her mouths "full of black Death" (Ancient Greek: πλεῖοι μέλανος Θανάτοιο, romanized: *pleîoi mélanos Thanátoio*).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] Seneca the Younger may have been the first to describe an epidemic as 'black death' (Latin: *mors atra*), but only in reference to the acute lethality and dark prognosis of disease.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The 12th–13th century French physician Gilles de Corbeil had already used *atra mors* to refer to a "pestilential fever" (*febris pestilentialis*) in his work *On the Signs and Symptoms of Diseases* (*De signis et symptomatibus aegritudium*).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The phrase *mors nigra*, 'black death', was used in 1350 by Simon de Covino (or Couvin), a Belgian astronomer, in his poem "On the Judgement of the Sun at a Feast of Saturn" (*De judicio Solis in convivio Saturni*), which attributes the plague to an astrological conjunction of Jupiter and Saturn.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] His use of the phrase is not connected unambiguously with the plague pandemic of 1347 and appears to refer to the fatal outcome of disease.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The historian Elizabeth Penrose, writing under the pen-name "Mrs Markham", described the 14th-century outbreak as the "black death" in 1823.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The historian Cardinal Francis Aidan Gasquet wrote about the Great Pestilence in 1893 and suggested that it had been "some form of the ordinary Eastern or bubonic plague".
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] In 1908, Gasquet said use of the name *atra mors* for the 14th-century epidemic first appeared in a 1631 book on Danish history by J.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] Pontanus: "Commonly and from its effects, they called it the black death" (Latin: *Vulgo & ab effectu atram mortem vocitabant*).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] Research from 2017 suggests plague first infected humans in Europe and Asia in the Late Neolithic to Early Bronze Age.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] Research in 2018 found evidence of *Yersinia pestis* in an ancient Swedish tomb, which may have been associated with the "Neolithic decline" around 3000BCE, in which European populations fell significantly.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] This *Y. pestis* may have been different from more modern types, with bubonic plague transmissible by fleas first known from Bronze Age remains near Samara.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] The symptoms of bubonic plague are first attested in a fragment of Rufus of Ephesus preserved by Oribasius; these ancient medical authorities suggest bubonic plague had appeared in the Roman Empire before the reign of Trajan, six centuries before arriving at Pelusium in the reign of Justinian I.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] In 2013, researchers confirmed earlier speculation that the cause of the plague of Justinian (541–549, with recurrences until 750) was *Y*.*pestis*.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] This is known as the first plague pandemic.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p01] Ole Jørgen Benedictow believes that this indicates it was an offshoot of the first plague pandemic which made its way eastward to Chinese territory by around 600.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] A report by the Medical Faculty of Paris stated that a conjunction of planets had caused "a great pestilence in the air" (miasma theory).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Some Muslim doctors cautioned against trying to prevent or treat a disease sent by God.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Others adopted preventive measures and treatments for plague used by Europeans.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] These Muslim doctors also depended on the writings of the ancient Greeks.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] , the organism responsible for spreading bubonic plague in most plague epidemics.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] which appears as a dark mass in the gut.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] is regurgitated into the wound, causing infection.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Due to climate change in Asia, rodents began to flee the dried-out grasslands to more populated areas, spreading the disease.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The plague disease, caused by the bacterium *Yersinia pestis*, is enzootic (commonly present) in populations of fleas carried by ground rodents, including marmots, in various areas, including Central Asia, Kurdistan, West Asia, North India, Uganda, and the western United States.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Definitive confirmation of the role of *Y. pestis* arrived in 2010 with a publication in *PLOS Pathogens* by Haensch et al.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] They assessed the presence of DNA/RNA with polymerase chain reaction (PCR) techniques for *Y. pestis* from the tooth sockets in human skeletons from mass graves in northern, central and southern Europe that were associated archaeologically with the Black Death and subsequent resurgences.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] In 2011 these results were further confirmed with genetic evidence derived from Black Death victims in the East Smithfield burial site in England.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Schuenemann et al. concluded in 2011 "that the Black Death in medieval Europe was caused by a variant of *Y. pestis* that may no longer exist".
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Later in 2011, Bos et al. reported in *Nature* the first draft genome of *Y. pestis* from plague victims from the same East Smithfield cemetery and indicated that the strain that caused the Black Death is ancestral to most modern strains of *Y. pestis*.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Later genomic papers have further confirmed the phylogenetic placement of the *Y. pestis* strain responsible for the Black Death as both the ancestor of later plague epidemics—including the third plague pandemic—and the descendant of the strain responsible for the Plague of Justinian.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] In addition, plague genomes from prehistory have been recovered.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] DNA taken from 25 skeletons from 14th-century London showed that plague is a strain of *Y. pestis* almost identical to that which hit Madagascar in 2013.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Further DNA evidence also proves the role of *Y. pestis* and traces the source to the Tian Shan mountains in Kyrgyzstan.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Researchers are hampered by a lack of reliable statistics from this period.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Most work has been done on the spread of the disease in England, where estimates of overall population at the start of the plague vary by over 100%, as no census was undertaken in England between the time of publication of the Domesday Book of 1086 and the poll tax of the year 1377.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Estimates of plague victims are usually extrapolated from figures for the clergy.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Mathematical modelling is used to match the spreading patterns and the means of transmission.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] In 2018 researchers suggested an alternative model in which "the disease was spread from human fleas and body lice to other people".
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The second model claims to better fit the trends of the plague's death toll, as the rat-flea-human hypothesis would have produced a delayed but very high spike in deaths, contradicting historical death data.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The Oriental rat flea has poor survival in cooler climates and reevaluation suggests the human flea was the principal vector of plague epidemics in Northern Europe.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Lars Walløe argued that these authors "take it for granted that Simond's infection model, black rat → rat flea → human, which was developed to explain the spread of plague in India, is the only way an epidemic of *Yersinia pestis* infection could spread".
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Similarly, Monica Green has argued that greater attention is needed to the range of (especially non-commensal) animals that might be involved in the transmission of plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] This theory is supported by research in 2018 which suggested transmission was more likely by body lice and fleas during the second plague pandemic.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Academic debate continues, but no single alternative explanation for the plague's spread has achieved widespread acceptance.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Many scholars arguing for *Y. pestis* as the major agent of the pandemic suggest that its extent and symptoms can be explained by a combination of bubonic plague with other diseases, including typhus, smallpox, and respiratory infections.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] In addition to the bubonic infection, others point to additional septicemic and pneumonic forms of plague, which lengthen the duration of outbreaks throughout the seasons and help account for its high mortality rate and additional recorded symptoms.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] In 2014, Public Health England announced the results of an examination of 25 bodies exhumed in the Clerkenwell area of London, as well as of wills registered in London during the period, which supported the pneumonic hypothesis.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Currently, while osteoarcheologists have conclusively verified the presence of *Y. pestis* bacteria in burial sites across northern Europe through examination of bones and dental pulp, no other epidemic pathogen has been discovered to bolster the alternative explanations.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] According to a team of medical geneticists led by Mark Achtman, *Yersinia pestis* "evolved in or near China" over 2,600 years ago.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Later research by a team led by Galina Eroshenko placed its origins more specifically in the Tian Shan mountains on the border between Kyrgyzstan and China.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] However more recent research notes that the previous sampling contained East Asian bias and that sampling since then has discovered strains of *Y. pestis* in the Caucasus region previously thought to be restricted to China.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] There is also no physical or specific textual evidence of the Black Death in 14th century China.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] As a result, China's place in the sequence of the plague's spread is still debated to this day.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] According to Charles Creighton, records of epidemics in 14th-century China suggest nothing more than typhus and major Chinese outbreaks of epidemic disease post-date the European epidemic by several years.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The earliest Chinese descriptions of the bubonic plague do not appear until the 1640s.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Epidemics killed an estimated 25 million across Asia during the fifteen years before the Black Death reached Constantinople in 1347.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] According to John Norris, evidence from Issyk-Kul indicates a small sporadic outbreak characteristic of transmission from rodents to humans with no wide-scale effect.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] According to Achtman, the dating of the plague suggests that it was not carried along the Silk Road, and its widespread appearance in that region probably postdates the European outbreak.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Additionally, the Silk Road had already been heavily disrupted before the spread of the Black Death; Western and Middle Eastern traders found it difficult to trade on the Silk Road by 1325 and impossible by 1340, making its role in the spread of plague less likely.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] There are no records of the symptoms of the Black Death from Mongol sources or writings from travelers east of the Black Sea prior to the Crimean outbreak in 1346.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The theory of Chinese origin implicates the Silk Road, the disease possibly spreading alongside Mongol armies and traders, or possibly arriving via ship—however, this theory is still contested.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] It is speculated that rats aboard Zheng He's ships in the 15th century may have carried the plague to Southeast Asia, India, and Africa.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Research on the Delhi Sultanate and the Yuan dynasty shows no evidence of any serious epidemic in 14th-century India and no specific evidence of plague in 14th-century China, suggesting that the Black Death may not have reached these regions.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Ole Benedictow argues that since the first clear reports of the Black Death come from Kaffa, the Black Death most likely originated in the nearby plague focus on the northwestern shore of the Caspian Sea.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Monica Green suggests that other parts of Eurasia outside the west do not contain the same evidence of the Black Death, because there were actually four strains of *Yersinia pestis* that became predominant in different parts of the world.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Mongol records of illness such as food poisoning may have been referring to the Black Death.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Another theory is that the plague originated near Europe and cycled through the Mediterranean, Northern Europe and Russia before making its way to China.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Other historians, such as John Norris and Ole Benedictaw, believe the plague likely originated in Europe or the Middle East, and never reached China.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Norris specifically argues for an origin in Kurdistan rather than Central Asia.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Plague was reportedly first introduced to Europe via Genoese traders from their port city of Kaffa in the Crimea in 1347.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] As the disease took hold, Genoese traders fled across the Black Sea to Constantinople, where the disease first arrived in Europe in summer 1347.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The epidemic there killed the 13-year-old son of the Byzantine emperor, John VI Kantakouzenos, who wrote a description of the disease modelled on Thucydides's account of the 5th century BCE Plague of Athens, noting the spread of the Black Death by ship between maritime cities.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Nicephorus Gregoras, while writing to Demetrios Kydones, described the rising death toll, the futility of medicine, and the panic of the citizens.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The first outbreak in Constantinople lasted a year, but the disease recurred ten times before 1400.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Carried by twelve Genoese galleys, plague arrived by ship in Sicily in October 1347; the disease spread rapidly all over the island.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Galleys from Kaffa reached Genoa and Venice in January 1348, but it was the outbreak in Pisa a few weeks later that was the entry point into northern Italy.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Towards the end of January, one of the galleys expelled from Italy arrived in Marseilles.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] From Italy, the disease spread northwest across Europe, striking France, Spain, Portugal, and England by June 1348, then spreading east and north through Germany, Scotland and Scandinavia from 1348 to 1350.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] It was introduced into Norway in 1349 when a ship landed at Askøy, then spread to Bjørgvin (modern Bergen).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Finally, it spread to northern Russia in 1352 and reached Moscow in 1353.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Plague was less common in parts of Europe with less-established trade relations, including the majority of the Basque Country, isolated parts of Belgium and the Netherlands, and isolated Alpine villages throughout the continent.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Among many other culprits of plague contagiousness, pre-existing malnutrition weakened the immune response, contributing to an immense decline in European population.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The disease struck various regions in the Middle East and North Africa during the pandemic, leading to serious depopulation and permanent change in both economic and social structures.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] By autumn 1347, plague had reached Alexandria in Egypt, transmitted by sea from Constantinople via a single merchant ship carrying slaves.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] By late summer 1348, it reached Cairo, capital of the Mamluk Sultanate, cultural center of the Islamic world, and the largest city in the Mediterranean Basin; the Bahriyya child sultan an-Nasir Hasan fled and more than a third of the 600,000 residents died.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The Nile was choked with corpses despite Cairo having a medieval hospital, the late 13th-century bimaristan of the Qalawun complex.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The historian al-Maqrizi described the abundant work for grave-diggers and practitioners of funeral rites; plague recurred in Cairo more than fifty times over the following one and a half centuries.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] During 1347, the disease travelled eastward to Gaza by April; by July it had reached Damascus, and in October plague had broken out in Aleppo.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] That year, in the territory of modern Lebanon, Syria, Israel, and Palestine, the cities of Ascalon, Acre, Jerusalem, Sidon, and Homs were all infected.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] In 1348–1349, the disease reached Antioch.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The city's residents fled to the north, but most of them ended up dying during the journey.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The pandemic spread westwards from Alexandria along the African coast, while in April 1348 Tunis was infected by ship from Sicily.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Tunis was then under attack by an army from Morocco; this army dispersed in 1348 and brought the contagion with them to Morocco, whose epidemic may also have been seeded from the Islamic city of Almería in al-Andalus.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Mecca became infected in 1348 by pilgrims performing the Hajj.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] In 1351 or 1352, the Rasulid sultan of the Yemen, al-Mujahid Ali, was released from Mamluk captivity in Egypt and carried plague with him on his return home.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] During 1349, records show the city of Mosul suffered a massive epidemic, and the city of Baghdad experienced a second round of the disease.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Symptoms of the plague include fever of 38–41 °C (100–106 °F), headaches, painful aching joints, nausea and vomiting, and a general feeling of malaise.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Left untreated, 80% of victims die within eight days.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Contemporary accounts of the pandemic are varied and often imprecise.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The most commonly noted symptom was the appearance of buboes (or *gavocciolos*) in the groin, neck and armpits, which oozed pus and bled when opened.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] This was followed by acute fever and vomiting of blood.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Most people died two to seven days after initial infection.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Freckle-like spots and rashes, which may have been caused by flea-bites, were identified as another potential sign of plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Lodewijk Heyligen, whose master Cardinal Giovanni Colonna died of plague in 1348, noted a distinct form of the disease, pneumonic plague, that infected the lungs and led to respiratory problems.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Symptoms include fever, cough and blood-tinged sputum.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] As the disease progresses, sputum becomes free-flowing and bright red.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Pneumonic plague has a mortality rate of 90–95%.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Septicemic plague is the least common of the three forms, with an untreated mortality rate near 100%.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Symptoms are high fevers and purple skin patches (purpura due to disseminated intravascular coagulation).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] In cases of pneumonic and particularly septicemic plague, the progress of the disease is so rapid that there would often be no time for the development of the enlarged lymph nodes that were noted as buboes.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] There are no exact figures for the death toll; the rate varied widely by locality.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Urban centers with higher populations suffered longer periods of abnormal mortality.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Some estimate that it may have killed between 75,000,000 and 200,000,000 people in Eurasia.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] A study published in 2022 of pollen samples across Europe from 1250 to 1450 was used to estimate changes in agricultural output before and after the Black Death.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The authors found great variability in different regions, with evidence for high mortality in areas of Scandinavia, France, western Germany, Greece, and central Italy, but uninterrupted agricultural growth in central and eastern Europe, Iberia, and Ireland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The Black Death killed, by various estimations, from 25 to 60% of Europe's population.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Robert Gottfried writes that as early as 1351, "agents for Pope Clement VI calculated the number of dead in Christian Europe at 23,840,000.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] With a preplague population of about 75 million, Clement's figure accounts for mortality of 31%-a rate about midway between the 50% mortality estimated for East Anglia, Tuscany, and parts of Scandinavia, and the less-than-15% morbidity for Bohemia and Galicia.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] And it is unerringly close to Froissart's claim that "a third of the world died," a measurement probably drawn from St.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] John's figure of mortality from plague in the Book of Revelation, a favorite medieval source of information." Ole J.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Benedictow proposes 60% mortality rate for Europe as a whole based on available data, with up to 80% based on poor nutritional conditions in the 14th century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] According to medieval historian Philip Daileader, it is likely that over four years, 45–50% of the European population died of plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The overwhelming number of deaths in Europe sometimes made mass burials necessary, and some sites had hundreds or thousands of bodies.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The mass burial sites that have been excavated have allowed archaeologists to continue interpreting and defining the biological, sociological, historical, and anthropological implications of the Black Death.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The mortality rate of the Black Death in the 14th century was far greater than the worst 20th-century outbreaks of *Y. pestis* plague, which occurred in India and killed as much as 3% of the population of certain cities.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] In 1348, the disease spread so rapidly that nearly a third of the European population perished before any physicians or government authorities had time to reflect upon its origins.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] In crowded cities, it was not uncommon for as much as 50% of the population to die.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Half of Paris's population of 100,000 people died.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] In Italy, the population of Florence was reduced from between 110,000 and 120,000 inhabitants in 1338 to 50,000 in 1351.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] At least 60% of the population of Hamburg and Bremen perished, and a similar percentage of Londoners may have died from the disease as well, leaving a death toll of approximately 62,000 between 1346 and 1353.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Florence's tax records suggest that 80% of the city's population died within four months in 1348.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Before 1350, there were about 170,000 settlements in Germany, and this was reduced by nearly 40,000 by 1450.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The disease bypassed some areas, with the most isolated areas being less vulnerable to contagion.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Plague did not appear in Flanders until the turn of the 15th century, and the impact was less severe on the populations of Hainaut, Finland, northern Germany, and areas of Poland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Monks, nuns, and priests were especially hard-hit since they cared for people ill with the plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The level of mortality in the rest of Eastern Europe was likely similar to that of Western Europe in the first outbreak, with descriptions suggesting a similar effect on Russian towns, and the cycles of plague in Russia being roughly equivalent.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] In 1382, the physician to the Avignon Papacy, Raimundo Chalmel de Vinario (Latin: *Magister Raimundus*, lit.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] 'Master Raymond'), observed the decreasing mortality rate of successive outbreaks of plague in 1347–1348, 1362, 1371 and 1382 in his treatise *On Epidemics* (*De epidemica*).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] By the 1380s in Europe, the plague predominantly affected children.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Chalmel de Vinario recognised that bloodletting was ineffective (though he continued to prescribe bleeding for members of the Roman Curia, whom he disliked), and said that all true cases of plague were caused by astrological factors and were incurable; he was never able to effect a cure.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The populations of some Italian cities, notably Florence, did not regain their pre-14th century size until the 19th century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The Black Death killed about 40% of Egypt's population.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] In Cairo, with a population numbering as many as 600,000, and possibly the largest city west of China, between one third and 40% of the inhabitants died within eight months.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] By the 18th century, the population of Cairo was halved from its numbers in 1347.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] It has been suggested that the Black Death, like other outbreaks through history, disproportionately affected the poorest people and those already in worse physical condition than the wealthier citizens.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] But along with population decline from the pandemic, wages soared in response to a subsequent labour shortage.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] However, many labourers, artisans, and craftsmen—those living from money-wages alone—suffered a reduction in real incomes owing to rampant inflation.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Landowners were also pushed to substitute monetary rents for labour services in an effort to keep tenants.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Taxes and tithes became difficult to collect, with living poor refusing to cover the share of the rich deceased, because many properties were empty and unfarmed, and because tax-collectors, where they could be employed, refused to go to plague spots.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The trade disruptions in the Mongol Empire caused by the Black Death was one of the reasons for its collapse.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] A study performed by Thomas Van Hoof of the Utrecht University suggests that the innumerable deaths brought on by the pandemic cooled the climate by freeing up land and triggering reforestation.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] This may have led to the Little Ice Age.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Renewed religious fervor and fanaticism increased in the wake of the Black Death.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Some Europeans targeted "various groups such as Jews, friars, foreigners, beggars, pilgrims", lepers, and Romani, blaming them for the crisis.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Lepers, and others with skin diseases such as acne or psoriasis, were killed throughout Europe.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Because 14th-century healers and governments were at a loss to explain or stop the disease, Europeans turned to astrological forces, earthquakes and the poisoning of wells by Jews as possible reasons for outbreaks.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Many believed the epidemic was a punishment by God for their sins, and could be relieved by winning God's forgiveness.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] There were many attacks against Jewish communities.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] In the Strasbourg massacre of February 1349, about 2,000 Jews were murdered.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] In August 1349, the Jewish communities in Mainz and Cologne were annihilated.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] By 1351, 60 major and 150 smaller Jewish communities had been destroyed.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] During this period many Jews relocated to Poland, where they received a welcome from King Casimir the Great.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] One theory that has been advanced is that the Black Death's devastation of Florence, between 1348 and 1350, resulted in a shift in the world view of people in 14th-century Italy that ultimately led to the Renaissance.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Italy was particularly badly hit by the pandemic, and the resulting familiarity with death may have caused thinkers to dwell more on their lives on Earth, rather than on spirituality and the afterlife.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] It has also been argued that the Black Death prompted a new wave of piety, manifested in the sponsorship of religious works of art.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] This does not fully explain why the Renaissance occurred in Italy in the 14th century; the Renaissance's emergence was most likely the result of the complex interaction of the above factors, in combination with an influx of Greek scholars after the fall of the Byzantine Empire.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] As a result of the drastic reduction in the populace the value of the working class increased, and commoners came to enjoy more freedom.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] To answer the increased need for labour, workers travelled in search of the most favorable position economically.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Prior to the emergence of the Black Death, the continent was considered a feudalistic society, composed of fiefs and city-states frequently managed by the Catholic Church.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The pandemic completely restructured both religion and political forces; survivors began to turn to other forms of spirituality and the power dynamics of the fiefs and city-states crumbled.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The survivors of the pandemic found not only that the prices of food were lower but also that lands were more abundant, and many of them inherited property from their dead relatives, and this probably contributed to the destabilization of feudalism.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The word "quarantine" has its roots in this period, though the practice of isolating people to prevent the spread of disease is older.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] In the city-state of Ragusa (modern Dubrovnik, Croatia), a thirty-day isolation period was implemented in 1377 for new arrivals to the city from plague-affected areas.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The isolation period was later extended to forty days, and given the name "quarantino" from the Italian word for "forty".
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Smaller monasteries and convents became unviable and closed.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Up to half parish churches lost their priest, apart from the parishioners.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The plague repeatedly returned to haunt Europe and the Mediterranean throughout the 14th to 17th centuries.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] According to Jean-Noël Biraben, the plague was present somewhere in Europe in every year between 1346 and 1671 (although some researchers have cautions about the uncritical use of Biraben's data).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Subsequent outbreaks, though severe, marked the plague's retreat from most of Europe (18th century) and North Africa (19th century).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Historian George Sussman argued that the plague had not occurred in East Africa until the 20th century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] However, other sources suggest that the second pandemic did indeed reach sub-Saharan Africa.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] More than 1.25 million deaths resulted from the extreme incidence of plague in 17th-century Spain.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The Black Death ravaged much of the Islamic world.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Plague could be found in the Islamic world almost every year between 1500 and 1850.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Sometimes the outbreaks affected small areas, while other outbreaks affected multiple regions.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Plague repeatedly struck the cities of North Africa.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Cairo suffered more than fifty plague epidemics within 150 years from the plague's first appearance, with the final outbreak of the second pandemic there in the 1840s.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Plague remained a major event in Ottoman society until the second quarter of the 19th century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Between 1701 and 1750, thirty-seven larger and smaller epidemics were recorded in Constantinople, and an additional thirty-one between 1751 and 1800.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Baghdad has suffered severely from visitations of the plague, and sometimes two-thirds of its population died.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The third plague pandemic (1855–1960) started in China in the mid-19th century, spreading to all inhabited continents and killing 10 million people in India alone.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The investigation of the pathogen that caused the 19th-century plague was begun by teams of scientists who visited Hong Kong in 1894, among whom was the French-Swiss bacteriologist Alexandre Yersin, for whom the pathogen was named.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Twelve plague outbreaks in Australia between 1900 and 1925 resulted in over 1,000 deaths, chiefly in Sydney.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] This led to the establishment of a Public Health Department there which undertook some leading-edge research on plague transmission from rat fleas to humans via the bacillus *Yersinia pestis*.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] The first North American plague epidemic was the San Francisco plague of 1900–1904, followed by another outbreak in 1907–1908.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Treatment methods include insecticides, the use of antibiotics, and a plague vaccine.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] It is feared that the plague bacterium could develop drug resistance and again become a major health threat.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] One case of a drug-resistant form of the bacterium was found in Madagascar in 1995.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] Another outbreak in Madagascar was reported in November 2014.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] In October 2017, the deadliest outbreak of the plague in modern times hit Madagascar, killing 170 people and infecting thousands.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/black-death-p02] An estimate of the case fatality rate for the modern plague, after the introduction of antibiotics, is 11%, although it may be higher in underdeveloped regions.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The three types of plague are the result of the route of infection: bubonic plague, septicemic plague, and pneumonic plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Bubonic plague is mainly spread by infected fleas from small animals.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] It may also result from exposure to the body fluids from a dead plague-infected animal.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Mammals such as rabbits, hares, and some cat species are susceptible to bubonic plague, and typically die upon contraction.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] In the bubonic form of plague, the bacteria enter through the skin through a flea bite and travel via the lymphatic vessels to a lymph node, causing it to swell.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Diagnosis is made by finding the bacteria in the blood, sputum, or fluid from lymph nodes.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Prevention is through public health measures such as not handling dead animals in areas where plague is common.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] While vaccines against the plague have been developed, the World Health Organization recommends that only high-risk groups, such as certain laboratory personnel and health care workers, get inoculated.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Several antibiotics are effective for treatment, including streptomycin, gentamicin, and doxycycline.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Without treatment, plague results in the death of 30% to 90% of those infected.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Death, if it occurs, is typically within 10 days.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] With treatment, the risk of death is around 10%.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Globally between 2010 and 2015 there were 3,248 documented cases, which resulted in 584 deaths.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The countries with the greatest number of cases are the Democratic Republic of the Congo, Madagascar, and Peru.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The plague is considered the likely cause of the Black Death that swept through Asia, Europe, and Africa in the 14th century and killed an estimated 50 million people, including about 25% to 60% of the European population.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Because the plague killed so many of the working population, wages rose due to the demand for labor.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Some historians see this as a turning point in European economic development.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The disease is also considered to have been responsible for the Plague of Justinian, originating in the Eastern Roman Empire in the 6th century CE, as well as the third epidemic, affecting China, Mongolia, and India, originating in the Yunnan Province in 1855.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The term *bubonic* is derived from the Greek word βουβών, meaning 'groin'.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The bubonic plague is an infection of the lymphatic system, usually resulting from the bite of an infected flea, *Xenopsylla cheopis* (the Oriental rat flea), though other flea species are able to carry the bubonic plague, such as *Pulex irritans* (the human flea) and *Ceratophyllus fasciatus*.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] *Xenopsylla cheopis* was the most effective flea species for transmission.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The flea is parasitic on house and field rats and seeks out other hosts when its rodent host dies.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Rats were an amplifying factor to bubonic plague due to their common association with humans (living around and within dwellings) as well as the nature of their blood, which allows the rat to withstand a major concentration of the plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The bacteria form aggregates in the gut of infected fleas, and this results in the flea regurgitating ingested blood, which is now infected, into the bite site of a rodent or human host.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Once established, the bacteria rapidly spread to the lymph nodes of the host and multiply.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The fleas that transmit the disease only directly infect humans when the rat population in the area is wiped out from a mass infection.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Furthermore, in areas with a large population of rats, individual rats can harbor low levels (subclinical) of the plague infection without causing human outbreaks.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] With no new rat inputs being added to the population from other areas, the infection only spread to humans in very rare cases of overcrowding.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] After being transmitted via the bite of an infected flea, the *Y. pestis* bacteria become localized in an inflamed lymph node, where they begin to colonize and reproduce.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Infected lymph nodes develop hemorrhages, which result in the death of tissue.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] *Y. pestis* bacilli can resist phagocytosis and even reproduce inside phagocytes and kill them.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] As the disease progresses, the lymph nodes can hemorrhage and become swollen and necrotic.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Bubonic plague can progress to lethal septicemic plague in some cases.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The plague is also known to spread to the lungs and become the disease known as the pneumonic plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The best-known symptom of bubonic plague is one or more infected, enlarged, and painful lymph nodes, known as buboes.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Buboes associated with the bubonic plague are commonly found in the armpits, upper femoral area, groin, and neck region.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] These buboes will grow and become more painful over time, often to the point of bursting.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Symptoms include heavy breathing, continuous vomiting of blood (hematemesis), aching limbs, coughing, and extreme pain caused by the decay or decomposition of the skin while the person is still alive.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Additional symptoms include extreme fatigue, gastrointestinal problems, spleen inflammation, lenticulae (black dots scattered throughout the body), delirium, coma, organ failure, and death.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Organ failure is a result of the bacteria infecting organs through the bloodstream.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Other forms of the disease include septicemic plague and pneumonic plague, in which the bacterium reproduces in the person's blood and lungs respectively.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Laboratory testing is required in order to diagnose and confirm plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Ideally, confirmation is through the identification of *Y. pestis* culture from a patient sample.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Confirmation of infection can be done by examining serum taken during the early and late stages of infection.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] To quickly screen for the *Y. pestis* antigen in patients, rapid dipstick tests have been developed for field use.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Bubonic plague outbreaks are controlled by pest control and modern sanitation techniques.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] This disease uses fleas commonly found on rats as a vector to jump from animals to humans.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The mortality rate is highest in the summer and early fall.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The successful control of rat populations in dense urban areas is essential to outbreak prevention.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] One example is the use of a machine called the Sulfurozador, used to deliver sulphur dioxide to eradicate the pest that spread the bubonic plague in Buenos Aires, Argentina during the early 18th century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Targeted chemoprophylaxis, sanitation, and vector control also played a role in controlling the 2003 Oran outbreak of the bubonic plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Another means of prevention in large European cities was a city-wide quarantine to not only limit interaction with people who were infected, but also to limit the interaction with the infected rats.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Several classes of antibiotic are effective in treating bubonic plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] These include aminoglycosides such as streptomycin and gentamicin, tetracyclines (especially doxycycline), and the fluoroquinolone ciprofloxacin.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Mortality associated with treated cases of bubonic plague is about 1–15%, compared to a mortality of 40–60% in untreated cases.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] People potentially infected with the plague need immediate treatment and should be given antibiotics within 24 hours of the first symptoms to prevent death.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Other treatments include oxygen, intravenous fluids, and respiratory support.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] People who have had contact with anyone infected by pneumonic plague are given prophylactic antibiotics.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Using the broad-based antibiotic streptomycin has proven to be dramatically successful against the bubonic plague within 12 hours of infection.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Globally between 2010 and 2015, there were 3,248 documented cases, which resulted in 584 deaths.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] For over a decade since 2001, Zambia, India, Malawi, Algeria, China, Peru, and the Democratic Republic of the Congo had the most plague cases, with over 1,100 cases in the Democratic Republic of the Congo alone.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] From 1,000 to 2,000 cases are conservatively reported per year to the WHO.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] From 2012 to 2017, reflecting political unrest and poor hygienic conditions, Madagascar began to host regular epidemics.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Between 1900 and 2015, the United States had 1,036 human plague cases, with an average of 9 cases per year.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] In 2015, 16 people in the western United States developed plague, including 2 cases in Yosemite National Park.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] These US cases usually occur in rural northern New Mexico, northern Arizona, southern Colorado, California, southern Oregon, and far western Nevada.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] In November 2017, the Madagascar Ministry of Health reported an outbreak to the WHO (World Health Organization) with more cases and deaths than any recent outbreak in the country.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Unusually, most of the cases were pneumonic rather than bubonic.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] In June 2018, a child was confirmed to be the first person in Idaho to be infected by bubonic plague in nearly 30 years.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] A couple died in May 2019, in Mongolia, while hunting marmots.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Another two people in the province of Inner Mongolia, China, were treated in November 2019 for the disease.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] In July 2020, in Bayannur, Inner Mongolia of China, a human case of bubonic plague was reported.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Officials responded by activating a city-wide plague-prevention system for the remainder of the year.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Also in July 2020, in Mongolia, a teenager died from bubonic plague after consuming infected marmot meat.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The first recorded epidemic affected the Sasanian Empire and their arch-rivals, the Eastern Roman Empire (Byzantine Empire) and was named the Plague of Justinian (541–549 AD) after emperor Justinian I, who was infected but survived through extensive treatment.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The pandemic resulted in the deaths of an estimated 25 million (6th century outbreak) to 50 million people (two centuries of recurrence).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The historian Procopius wrote, in Volume II of *History of the Wars*, of his personal encounter with the plague and the effect it had on the rising empire.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] In the spring of 542, the plague arrived in Constantinople, working its way from port city to port city and spreading around the Mediterranean Sea, later migrating inland eastward into Asia Minor and west into Greece and Italy.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The Plague of Justinian is said to have been "completed" in the middle of the 8th century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Because the infectious disease spread inland by the transferring of merchandise through Justinian's efforts in acquiring luxurious goods of the time and exporting supplies, his capital became the leading exporter of the bubonic plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Procopius, in his work *Secret History*, declared that Justinian was a demon of an emperor who either created the plague himself or was being punished for his sinfulness.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Medieval society's increasing population was put to deadly halt when, in the Late Middle Ages, Europe experienced the deadliest disease outbreak in history.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] They called it the Great Dying or The Great Pestilence, later coined The Black Death.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Lasting in potency for roughly six years, 1346–1352, the Black Death claimed one-third of the European human population, with mortality rates as high as 70%–80%.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Some historians believe that society subsequently became more violent as the mass mortality rate cheapened life and thus increased warfare, crime, popular revolt, waves of flagellants, and persecution.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The Black Death originated in Central Asia and spread from Italy and then throughout other European countries.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Arab historians Ibn Al-Wardni and Almaqrizi believed the Black Death originated in Mongolia.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Chinese records also show a huge outbreak in Mongolia in the early 1330s.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] In 2022, researchers presented evidence that the plague originated near Lake Issyk-Kul in Kyrgyzstan.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The Mongols had cut the trade route (the Silk Road) between China and Europe, which halted the spread of the Black Death from eastern Russia to Western Europe.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The European epidemic may have begun with the siege of Caffa, an attack that Mongols launched on the Italian merchants' last trading station in the region, Caffa, in the Crimea.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] In late 1346, plague broke out among the besiegers and from them penetrated the town.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The Mongol forces catapulted plague-infested corpses into Caffa as a form of attack, one of the first known instances of biological warfare.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] When spring arrived, the Italian merchants fled on their ships, unknowingly carrying the Black Death.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Carried by the fleas on rats, the plague initially spread to humans near the Black Sea and then outwards to the rest of Europe as a result of people fleeing from one area to another.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Rats migrated with humans, traveling among grain bags, clothing, ships, wagons, and grain husks.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Continued research indicates that black rats, those that primarily transmitted the disease, prefer grain as a primary meal.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Due to this, the major bulk grain fleets that transported major city's food shipments from Africa and Alexandria to heavily populated areas, and were then unloaded by hand, played a role in increasing the transmission effectiveness of the plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The plague resurfaced for a third time in the mid-19th century; this is also known as "the modern pandemic".
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Like the two previous outbreaks, this one also originated in Eastern Asia, most likely in Yunnan, a province of China, where there are several natural plague foci.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The initial outbreaks occurred in the second half of the 18th century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The disease remained localized in Southwest China for several years before spreading.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] In the city of Canton, beginning in January 1894, the disease had killed 80,000 people by June.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Daily water traffic with the nearby city of Hong Kong rapidly spread the plague there, killing over 2,400 within two months during the 1894 Hong Kong plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The third pandemic spread the disease to port cities throughout the world in the second half of the 19th century and the early 20th century via shipping routes.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The plague infected people in Chinatown in San Francisco from 1900 to 1904, and in the nearby locales of Oakland and the East Bay again from 1907 to 1909.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] During the former outbreak, in 1902, authorities made permanent the Chinese Exclusion Act, a law originally signed into existence by President Chester A.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The Act was supposed to last for 10 years, but was renewed in 1892 with the Geary Act, then followed by the 1902 decision.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The last major outbreak in the United States occurred in Los Angeles in 1924, though the disease is still present in wild rodents and can be passed to humans who come in contact with them.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] According to the World Health Organization, the pandemic was considered active until 1959, when worldwide casualties dropped to 200 per year.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] In 1994, a plague outbreak in five Indian states caused an estimated 700 infections (including 52 deaths) and triggered a large migration of Indians within India as they tried to avoid the disease.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] It was during the 1894 Hong Kong plague outbreak that Alexandre Yersin isolated the bacterium responsible (*Yersinia pestis*), a few days after Japanese bacteriologist Kitasato Shibasaburō had isolated it.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] However, the latter's description was imprecise and also expressed doubts of its relation to the disease, and thus the bacterium is today only named after Yersin.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The scale of death and social upheaval associated with plague outbreaks has made the topic prominent in many historical and fictional accounts since the disease was first recognized.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The Black Death in particular is described and referenced in numerous contemporary sources, some of which, including works by Chaucer, Boccaccio, and Petrarch, are considered part of the Western canon.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] *The Decameron*, by Boccaccio, is notable for its use of a frame story involving individuals who have fled Florence for a secluded villa to escape the Black Death.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] First-person, sometimes sensationalized or fictionalized, accounts of living through plague years have also been popular across centuries and cultures.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] For example, Samuel Pepys's diary makes several references to his first-hand experiences of the Great Plague of London in 1665–66.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Some of the earliest instances of biological warfare were said to have been products of the plague, as armies of the 14th century were recorded catapulting diseased corpses over the walls of towns and villages to spread the pestilence.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] This was done by Jani Beg when he attacked the city of Kaffa in 1347.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Later, plague was used during the Second Sino-Japanese War as a bacteriological weapon by the Imperial Japanese Army.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] These weapons were provided by Shirō Ishii's units and used in experiments on humans before being used in the field.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] For example, in 1940, the Imperial Japanese Army Air Service bombed Ningbo with fleas carrying the bubonic plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] During the Khabarovsk War Crime Trials, the accused, such as Major General Kiyoshi Kawashima, testified that, in 1941, 40 members of Unit 731 air-dropped plague-contaminated fleas on Changde.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] These operations caused epidemic plague outbreaks.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Substantial research has been done regarding the origin of the plague and how it traveled through the continent.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Mitochondrial DNA of modern rats in Western Europe indicated that these rats came from two different areas, one being Africa and the other unclear.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] The research regarding this pandemic has greatly increased with technology.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Through archaeo-molecular investigation, researchers have discovered the DNA of plague bacillus in the dental core of those that fell ill to the plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Analysis of teeth of the deceased allows researchers to further understand both the demographics and mortuary patterns of the disease.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] For example, in 2013 in England, archeologists uncovered a burial mound to reveal 17 bodies, mainly children, who had died of the Bubonic plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] They analyzed these burial remains using radiocarbon dating to determine they were from the 1530s, and dental core analysis revealed the presence of Yersinia pestis.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Other evidence for rats that are currently still being researched consists of gnaw marks on bones, predator pellets and rat remains that were preserved in situ.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] This research allows individuals to trace early rat remains to track the path traveled and in turn connect the impact of the Bubonic Plague to specific breeds of rats.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Burial sites, known as plague pits, offer archaeologists an opportunity to study the remains of people who died from the plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] Another research study indicates that these separate pandemics were all interconnected.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] A current computer model indicates that the disease did not go away between these pandemics.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/bubonic-plague] It rather lurked within the rat population for years without causing human epidemics.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] A **burgh** (/ˈbʌrə/ *BURR-ə*) is an autonomous municipal corporation in Scotland, usually a city, town, or **toun** in Scots.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] This type of administrative division existed from the 12th century, when King David I created the first royal burghs.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Burgh status was broadly analogous to borough status, found in the rest of the United Kingdom.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Following local government reorganisation in 1975, the title of "royal burgh" remains in use in many towns, but now has little more than ceremonial value.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] 1124–53) had established other burghs including Edinburgh, Stirling, Dunfermline, Haddington, Perth, Dumfries, Jedburgh, Montrose, Rutherglen and Lanark.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Most of the burghs granted charters in his reign probably already existed as settlements.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Charters were copied almost verbatim from those used in England, and early burgesses usually invited English and Flemish settlers.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] They were able to impose tolls and fines on traders within a region outside their settlements.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Properties known as Burgage tenures were a key feature, whose tenants had to be of the Burgher class, known as a "Burgesses", and therefore eligible to participate in trade within the town, and to elect town officials.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] In the south-west, Glasgow, Ayr and Kirkcudbright were aided by the less profitable sea trade with Ireland and to a lesser extent France and Spain.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Burghs were typically settlements under the protection of a castle and usually had a market place, with a widened high street or junction, marked by a mercat cross, beside houses for the burgesses and other inhabitants.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The founding of 16 royal burghs can be traced to the reign of David I (1124–53) and there is evidence of 55 burghs by 1296.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] In addition to the major royal burghs, the late Middle Ages saw the proliferation of baronial and ecclesiastical burghs, with 51 created between 1450 and 1516.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Most of these were much smaller than their royal counterparts.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Excluded from foreign trade, they acted mainly as local markets and centres of craftsmanship.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Burghs were centres of basic crafts, including the manufacture of shoes, clothes, dishes, pots, joinery, bread and ale, which would normally be sold to "indwellers" and "outdwellers" on market days.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] In general, burghs carried out far more local trading with their hinterlands, on which they relied for food and raw materials, than trading nationally or abroad.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Burghs had rights to representation in the Parliament of Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Under the Acts of Union of 1707 many became parliamentary burghs, represented in the Parliament of Great Britain.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Under the Scottish Reform Act 1832, 32 years after the merger of the Parliament of Great Britain into the Parliament of the United Kingdom, the boundaries of burghs for parliamentary elections ceased to be necessarily their boundaries for other purposes.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Until 1833, each burgh had a different constitution or "sett".
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The government of the burgh was often in the hands of a self-nominating corporation, and few local government functions were performed: these were often left to ad hoc bodies.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Two pieces of reforming legislation were enacted in 1833: The Royal Burghs (Scotland) Act 1833 (3 & 4 Will.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] 76) and the Burgh Police (Scotland) Act 1833 (3 & 4 Will.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The Royal Burghs (Scotland) Act 1833 (3 & 4 Will.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] 76) provided for the election of magistrates and councillors.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Each burgh was to have a common council consisting of a provost (or lord provost), magistrates (or bailies) and councillors.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Every parliamentary elector living within the "royalty" or area of the royal burgh, or within seven statute miles of its boundary, was entitled to vote in burgh elections.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] One third of the common council was elected each year.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The councillors selected a number of their members to be bailies, who acted as a magistrates bench for the burgh and dealt with such issues as licensing.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The provost, or chief magistrate, was elected from among the council every three years.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The Royal Burghs Act was also extended to the 12 parliamentary burghs which had recently been enfranchised.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] These were growing industrial centres, and apart from the lack of a charter, they had identical powers and privileges to the royal burghs.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Royal Burghs retained the right to corporate property or "common good".
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] This property was used for the advantage of the inhabitants of the burgh, funding such facilities as public parks, museums and civic events.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The Burgh Police (Scotland) Act 1833 (3 & 4 Will.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] 46) allowed the inhabitants of royal burghs, burghs of regality and of barony to adopt a "police system".
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] "Police" in this sense did not refer to law enforcement, but to various local government activities summarised in the act as *"paving, lighting, cleansing, watching, supplying with water, and improving such Burghs respectively, as may be necessary and expedient"*.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The act could be adopted following its approval in a poll of householders in the burgh.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Burghs reformed or created under this and later legislation became known as police burghs.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The governing body of a police burgh were the police commissioners.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The commissioners were elected by the existing town council of the burgh, not by the electorate at large.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The town council of a burgh could by a three-quarters majority become police commissioners for the burgh.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] In many cases this led to the existence of two parallel burgh administrations, the town council and the police commissioners, each with the same membership, but separate legal identity and powers.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Further legislation, the Police (Scotland) Act 1850 (13 & 14 Vict. c.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] 33), allowed "populous places" other than existing burghs to become police burghs.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] In 1893, most of the anomalies in the administration of burghs were removed: police commissioners were retitled as councillors and all burghs were to consist of a single body corporate, ending the existence of parallel burghs.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] All burghs of barony and regality that had not adopted a police system were abolished.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Councils were to be headed by a chief magistrate using the "customary title" of the burgh.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] In 1900, the chief magistrate of every burgh was to be known as the provost – except in burghs granted a lord provost.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The last major legislation to effect burghs came into effect in 1930.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The Local Government (Scotland) Act 1929 (19 & 20 Geo.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The Local Government (Scotland) Act 1973 (c.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The common good properties and funds of the royal burghs continue to exist.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] They are administered by the present area councils, who must make "have regard to the interests of the inhabitants of the area to which the common good formerly related".
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The use of these assets are to be for the benefit of the inhabitants of the former burgh.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Any person or body holding the honorary freedom *of any place... formerly having the status of a city, burgh or royal burgh* continued to enjoy that status after the 1975 reorganisation.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The chief magistrate or convener of a burgh, equivalent to a mayor, was called a provost.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Many different titles were in use until the Town Councils (Scotland) Act 1900 standardised the term as "provost", except in cities with a lord provost.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Since 1975 local authorities have been free to choose the title of their convener and provosts are appointed to chair a number of area and community councils.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Under the provost were magistrates or baillies who both acted as councillors, and in the enforcement of laws.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] As well as general tasks, they often had specific tasks such as inspecting wine, or ale, or other products sold at market.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The title of bailie ceased to have any statutory meaning in 1975, although modern area councils do sometimes make appointments to the office on a purely ceremonial basis.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] For example, Glasgow City Council grants the title in an honorary capacity to senior councillors, while Stirling Council appoints four bailies to act in lieu of the provost in specific geographical areas.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] A resident granted the rights of a "freeman" of the burgh, was styled a burgess (*pl. burgesses*), a title also used in English boroughs.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] These freemen and their wives were a class which did not include dependants (e.g. apprentices) and servants, though they were not guaranteed to be wealthy.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] This was a title held by one of the bailies of the burgh who presided over a Dean of Guild Court which was given the specific duty of building control.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The courts were abolished in 1975, with building regulation transferred to the relevant local authority.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Appointments to the office of Dean of Guild are still made in some areas: for instance the Lord Dean of Guild of Glasgow is described as the "second citizen of Glasgow" after the Lord Provost although the appointment is in the hands of the Merchants House of Glasgow, and not the city council.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Early Burghs were granted the power to trade, which allowed them to control trade until the 19th century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The population of burgesses could be roughly divided between merchants and craftsmen, and the tensions between the interests of the two classes was often a feature of the cities.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Craftsmen were usually organised into guilds.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Merchants also had a guild, but many merchants did not belong to it, and it would be run by a small group of the most powerful merchants.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The class of merchants included all traders, from stall-holders and pack-men to shop-holders and traders of considerable wealth.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] As used in this article, the Scots language word *burgh* is derived from the Old English *Burh*.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] In Scotland it refers to corporate entities whose legality is peculiar to Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] (Scottish law was protected and preserved as distinct from laws of England under the Acts of Union of 1707.) Another variant pronunciation, /brʌf/ ⓘ, is heard in several Cumbrian place names, e.g.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Burgh by Sands, Longburgh, Drumburgh, Mayburgh Henge.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The Old English word was originally used for a fortified town or proto-castle (e.g. at Dover Castle or Burgh Castle) and was related to the verb *beorgan* (cf.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Dutch and German *bergen*) 'to keep, save, make secure'.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] In the German language, *Burg* means 'castle' or 'fortress', though so many towns grew up around castles that it almost came to mean *city*, and is incorporated into many placenames, such as Hamburg, Flensburg and Strasburg.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The word has cognates in other Germanic languages.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] For example, *burg* in German, and *borg* in both Danish and Swedish.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The equivalent word is also to be found in Frisian, Dutch, Norwegian, Icelandic and Faroese.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Burgh in placenames is found in its greatest UK concentration in the East Anglia region of southern England, where also the word has taken the form *bury*, as in Canterbury.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] A number of other European languages have cognate words which were borrowed from the Germanic languages during the Middle Ages, including *brog* in Irish, *bwr* or *bwrc*, meaning 'wall, rampart' in Welsh, *bourg* in French, *borgo* in Italian, and *burgo* in Spanish (hence the place-name Burgos).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] The most obviously derivative words are burgher in English, *Bürger* in German or *burger* in Dutch (literally 'citizen', with connotations of middle-class in English and other Germanic languages).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] Also related are the words *bourgeois* and *belfry* (both from the French), and *burglar*.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/burgh] More distantly, it is related to words meaning 'hill' or 'mountain' in a number of languages (cf. the second element of *iceberg*).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] Roman historians, including Tacitus and Cassius Dio, referred to the territory north of the River Forth as "Caledonia", and described it as inhabited by the Maeatae and the Caledonians (Latin: *Caledonii*).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] In 1824, Scottish antiquarian George Chalmers posited that *Caledonia* derived from *Cal-ydon*, the name of a Greek province famous for its forests.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] He hypothesized that classical writers such as Tacitus later applied this name to the Scottish Highlands as another area of woods.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] This derivation is no longer accepted by modern linguists.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] According to linguist Stefan Zimmer, *Caledonia* is derived from the tribal name *Caledones* (a Latinization of a Brittonic nominative plural n-stem *Calēdones* or *Calīdones*, from earlier **Kalē=Black River=don/Danue Goddess[i]oi*).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] He etymologises this name as perhaps 'possessing hard feet' ("alluding to standfastness or endurance"), from the Proto-Celtic roots **kal-* 'hard' and **pēd-* 'foot', with **pēd-* contracting to *-ed-*.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] The singular form of the ethnic name is attested as *Caledo* (a Latinization of the Brittonic nominative singular n-stem **Calidū*) on a Romano-British inscription from Colchester.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] However, some authors have doubted the link between *Calidones* and *kalet-* 'hard', especially in light of the theory that the Caledonians and Picts might not have been Celtic speakers.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] The name of the Caledonians may be found in toponymy, such as *Dùn Chailleann*, the Scottish Gaelic name of the town of Dunkeld, meaning 'fort of the Caledonii', and possibly in that of the mountain *Sìdh Chailleann*, the 'fairy hill of the Caledonians'.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] According to *Historia Brittonum*, the site of the seventh battle of the legendary King Arthur was a forest in what is now Scotland, called *Coit Celidon* in early Welsh.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] The name seems to relate to that of a large central Brythonic tribe, the *Caledonii*, one amongst several in the area and perhaps the dominant tribe, which would explain the binomial Caledonia/Caledonii.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] The modern use of "Caledonia" in English and Scots is either as a historical description of northern Britain during the Roman era or as a romantic or poetic name for Scotland as a whole.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] The name has been widely used by organisations and commercial entities.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] Notable examples include Glasgow Caledonian University, ferry operator Caledonian MacBrayne, and the now-defunct British Caledonian airline and Caledonian Railway.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] The Caledonian Sleeper is an overnight train service from London to Scottish destinations.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] The Inverness Caledonian Thistle F.C. is a professional football club.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] In music, "Caledonia" is a popular Scottish patriotic song and folk ballad written by Dougie MacLean in 1977 and published in 1979 on an album of the same name; it has since been covered by various other artists, most notably Frankie Miller and Van Morrison.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] An original rock piece titled Caledonia appeared on Robin Trower's fourth album, "Long Misty Days", where coincidentally Frankie Miller cowrote another track on that album.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] The web series *Caledonia* and associated novel is a supernatural police drama that takes place in Glasgow, Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] Ptolemy's account in his *Geography* also referred to the *Caledonia Silva*, an idea still recalled in the modern expression "Caledonian Forest", although the woods are much reduced in size since Roman times.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] Some scholars point out that the name "Scotland" is ultimately derived from Scotia, a Latin term first used for Ireland (also called Hibernia by the Romans) and later for Scotland, the Scoti peoples having originated in Ireland and resettled in Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] Another, post-conquest, Roman name for the island of Great Britain was Albion, which is cognate with the Scottish Gaelic name for Scotland: *Alba*.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] There is an emerging trend to use the term Caledonia to describe New Caledonia in English, which reflects the usage in French of Calédonie (where the full name is La Nouvelle-Calédonie).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/caledonia] The New Caledonian trade and investment department promotes inward investment with the slogan "Choose Caledonia".
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The **demographic history of Scotland** includes all aspects of population history in what is now Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The earliest surviving archaeological evidence of human settlement is of Mesolithic hunter-gatherer encampments.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] These suggest a highly mobile boat-using people, probably with a very low density of population.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Neolithic farming brought permanent settlements dating from 3500 BC, and greater concentrations of population.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Evidence of hillforts and other buildings suggest a growing settled population.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Changes in the extent of woodland indicates that the Roman invasions from the first century AD had a negative impact on the native population.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] There are almost no written sources from which to reconstruct the demography of early medieval Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] This was probably a high fertility, high mortality society, similar to developing countries in the modern world.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The population may have grown from half a million to a million by the mid-fourteenth century when the Black Death reached the country.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] It may then have fallen to as low as half a million by the end of the fifteenth century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Roughly half lived north of the River Tay and perhaps 10 per cent in the burghs that grew up in the later medieval period.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Inflation in prices, indicating greater demand, suggests that the population continued to grow until the late sixteenth century, when it probably levelled off.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] It began to grow again in the relative stability of the late seventeenth century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The earliest reliable evidence suggests a population of 1.2 million in 1681.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] This was probably reduced by the "seven ill years" of the 1690s, which caused severe famine and depopulation, particularly in the north.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The first national census was conducted in 1755, and showed the population of Scotland as 1,265,380.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] By then four towns had populations of over 10,000, with the capital, Edinburgh, the largest with 57,000 inhabitants.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Overall the population of Scotland grew rapidly in the late eighteenth and nineteenth centuries.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Whilst the Lowland Clearances caused depopulation in the affected areas, only local net population reductions occurred in the Highlands during the Highland Clearances.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] By the beginning of the twentieth century, one in three lived in the four cities of Glasgow, Edinburgh, Dundee and Aberdeen.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Glasgow emerged as the largest city, with a population of 762,000 by 1901, making it "the Second City of the Empire".
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Despite industrial expansion there were insufficient jobs and between the mid-nineteenth century and the Great Depression from 1929-39 about two million Scots emigrated to North America and Australia, and another 750,000 to England.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The Scots were only 10 per cent of the British population but they provided 15 per cent of the national armed forces, and eventually accounted for 20 per cent of the dead in World War I (1914–18).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] With the end of mass migration, the population reached a peak of 5,240,800 in 1974.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Thereafter it began to fall slowly, moving down to 5,062,940 in 2000.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] There was also a decrease in some urban populations as a result of policies of slum clearance, overspill and relocation to new towns, with the population of Glasgow falling from over one million in 1951 to 629,000 in 2001.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Rural areas also saw a loss of population, particularly in the Highlands and Hebrides islands.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] At times during the last interglacial period (130,000– 70,000 BC) Europe had a climate warmer than today's, and early humans may have made their way to what is now Scotland, though archaeologists have found no traces of this.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Glaciers then scoured their way across most of Britain, and only after the ice retreated did Scotland again become habitable, around 9600 BC.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Mesolithic hunter-gatherer encampments formed the first known settlements, and archaeologists have dated a site near Biggar to around 8500 BC.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Numerous other sites found around Scotland build up a picture of highly mobile boat-using people making tools from bone, stone and antlers, probably with a very low density of population.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Neolithic farming brought permanent settlements, such as the stone house at Knap of Howar on Papa Westray dating from 3500 BC, and greater concentrations of population.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Although the Roman geographer Ptolemy indicated that there were 19 "towns" in Caledonia, north of the Roman province of Britannia, no clear evidence of urban settlements has been found and these were probably hillforts.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] There is evidence of over 1,000 such forts, most south of the Clyde-Forth line, but the majority seem to have been abandoned in the Roman period.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] There is also evidence of distinctive stone wheelhouses (a type of roundhouse, with a circle of stone piers resembling the spokes of a wheel) and over 400 small underground souterrains (underground galleries that may have been used to store food).
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Extensive analyses of Black Loch in Fife indicate that arable land spread at the expense of forest from about 2000 BCuntil the time of the Roman advance into lowland Scotland in the first century AD, suggesting an expanding settled population.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Thereafter, there was regrowth of birch, oak and hazel for some 500 years, suggesting that the Roman invasions had a negative impact on the native population.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Estimates have been made of a population of 10,000 in Dál Riata and 80–100,000 for Pictland, which was probably the largest region.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] It is likely that the fifth and sixth centuries saw higher mortality rates due to the appearance of bubonic plague, which may have reduced the population.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The examination of burial sites for this period, such as that at Hallowhill, St Andrews, indicates a life expectancy at birth of only 26 to 29.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] This would have meant a relatively low ratio of available workers to the number of mouths to feed, which in turn would have made it difficult to produce a surplus that would allow demographic growth and the development of more complex societies.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] From the formation of the Kingdom of Alba in the tenth century, to before the Black Death reached the country in 1349, estimates based on the amount of farmable land suggest that the population may have grown from half a million to a million.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Growth was probably punctuated by occasional crises, like the famines recorded in chronicles for 1154 and 1256.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] More significant was a series of poor harvests that affected Scotland and most of Europe in the early fourteenth century and widespread famines in 1315–16 and in the later 1330s.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Although there is no reliable documentation of the demographic impact of the Black Death in Scotland, there are some indications of the immediate effects of the plague.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Walter Bower recorded that 24, about a third, of the canons of St.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] There are also anecdotal references to abandoned land in the following decades.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] If the pattern followed that in England, then the population may have fallen to as low as half a million by the end of the fifteenth century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Compared with the distribution of population after the later Clearances and the Industrial Revolution, these numbers would have been relatively evenly spread over the kingdom, with roughly half living north of the River Tay.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Price inflation, which generally reflects growing demand for food, suggests that the population was probably still expanding in the first half of the sixteenth century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Almost half the years in the second half of the sixteenth century saw local or national scarcity, necessitating the shipping of large quantities of grain from the Baltic.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Distress was exacerbated by outbreaks of plague, with major epidemics in the periods 1584-8, 1595 and 1597–1609.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The population expansion probably levelled off after the famine of the 1590s, as prices were relatively stable in the early seventeenth century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Famine was common, with four periods of famine prices between 1620 and 1625.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] There is evidence that there was a different demographic regime operating in the Highlands, where growth probably continued from the early seventeenth century to the late eighteenth century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Estimates based on hearth tax returns for 1691 indicate a population of around 1.2 million.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The population may have been seriously affected by the failed harvests (1695, 1696 and 1698-9) known as the "seven ill years".
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The result was severe famine and depopulation, particularly in the north.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Starvation probably killed 5 to 15 per cent of the Scottish population, but in areas like Aberdeenshire death rates reached 25 per cent.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The famines of the 1690s were seen as particularly severe, partly because famine had become relatively rare in the second half of the seventeenth century, with only one year of dearth (in 1674), and the shortages of the 1690s were the last of their kind.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Between 1650 and 1700 approximately 7,000 Scots migrated to America, 10–20,000 to Europe and England and 60–100,000 to Ireland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The first reliable figure for the national population is from the census conducted by the Reverend Alexander Webster in 1755, which showed the inhabitants of Scotland as 1,265,380 persons.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Unlike in England, where the nucleated village existed relatively early, most of the early modern population of Scotland, in both the Lowlands and Highlands, was housed in small clachans or townships and isolated dwellings.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] These were unstructured groups of houses, often belonging to between four and six tenants, who were often engaged in common agriculture.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] As the population expanded, some of these settlements were subdivided to create new clachans and more marginal land was settled, with *sheilings* (clusters of huts occupied while summer pasture was being used for grazing) becoming permanent settlements.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Perhaps 10 per cent of the population lived in the burghs that had grown up in the later medieval period, mainly in the east and south of the country.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] They perhaps had an average population of 2,000, but many were much smaller than 1,000, and the largest, Edinburgh, probably had a population of over 10,000 at the beginning of the period.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Edinburgh doubled in size in the century after 1540, particularly after the plague of 1580, with most of its population probably coming from a growing reservoir in the surrounding countryside.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] It also expanded beyond the city walls in suburbs at Cowgate, Bristo and Westport and by 1750, with its suburbs, it had reached a population of 57,000.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The only other towns above 10,000 by the end of the period were Glasgow with 32,000, Aberdeen with around 16,000 and Dundee with 12,000.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] By 1600 Scotland had a higher proportion of its population living in larger towns than contemporaneous Scandinavia, Switzerland and most of Eastern Europe: by 1750 in Europe, only Italy, the Low Countries and England were more urbanised than Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The agricultural revolution changed the traditional system of agriculture which had existed in Lowland Scotland.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Thousands of cottars and tenant farmers migrated from farms and smallholdings to the new industrial centres of Glasgow, Edinburgh and northern England.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Particularly after the end of the boom created by the Revolutionary and Napoleonic Wars (1790–1815), Highland landlords needed cash to maintain their position in London society.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Whereas rents had often been paid in kind, the landlords turned to money rents.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] They evicted the farmers who had occupied run rig arable land and shared grazing.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Their holdings were let to large scale sheep farmers, who could afford substantially higher rents.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The eviction of tenants went against **dùthchas**, the principle that clan members had an inalienable right to rent land in the clan territory.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Particularly in the north and west Highlands, estates offered alternative accommodation in newly established crofting communities, with the intention that the resettled tenants worked in fishing or the kelp industry.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] These evictions were the first phase of the Highland Clearances.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The total population of the Highlands continued to rise throughout the clearances.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The result was a continuous exodus from the land—to the cities, and further afield to England, Canada, America and Australia.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The Great Famine of Ireland of the 1840s, caused by potato blight, which devastated the population of Ireland, reached the Highlands in 1846.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The overcrowded crofting communities were highly dependent on the potato.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Although 150,000 people faced disaster, they were rescued by an effective emergency relief system that stands in dramatic contrast to the failures of relief in Ireland and prevented a major demographic crisis.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] By the time of the first decadal census in 1801, the population was 1,608,420.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] While population fell in some rural areas, it rose rapidly in the towns.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Aberdeen, Dundee and Glasgow grew by a third or more between 1755 and 1775 and the textile town of Paisley more than doubled its population.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Because of the industrial revolution, Scotland was already one of the most urbanised societies in Europe by 1800.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] In 1800, 17 per cent of people in Scotland lived in towns of more than 10,000 inhabitants.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] By 1850 it was 32 per cent and by 1900 it was 50 per cent.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] By 1900 one in three of the entire population were in the four cities of Glasgow, Edinburgh, Dundee and Aberdeen.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] This was due to a high birth rate and immigration from the countryside and particularly from Ireland; but from the 1870s there was a fall in the birth rate and lower rates of migration and much of the growth was due to longer life expectancy.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Glasgow was now one of the largest cities in the world, and it became known as "the Second City of the Empire" after London.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Mortality rates were high compared with England and other European nations.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Evidence suggests a national death rate of 30 per 1,000 in 1755, 24 in the 1790s and 22 in the early 1860s.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Mortality tended to be much higher in urban than rural settlements.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] The first time these were measured, 1861–82, in the four major cities these were 28.1 per 1,000 and 17.9 in rural areas.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Mortality probably peaked in Glasgow in the 1840s, when large inflows of population from the Highlands and Ireland combined population outgrowing sanitary provision and combining with outbreaks of epidemic disease.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] National rates began to fall in the 1870s, particularly in the cities, as environmental conditions improved.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] By 1930–32 the national rate was 13.4 per 1,000, with a rate of 14.1 and in rural areas 12.8.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Even with the growth of industry there were not enough good jobs: as a result, from 1841 to 1931, about two million Scots emigrated to North America and Australia, and another 750,000 Scots relocated to England.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] With a population of 4.8 million in 1911, Scotland sent 690,000 men to the First World War, of whom 74,000 died in combat or from disease, and 150,000 were seriously wounded.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Thus, although Scots were only 10 per cent of the British population, they made up 15 per cent of the national armed forces and eventually accounted for 8.3% of the UK's 887,858 dead from all causes.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] While emigration began to tail off in England and Wales after the First World War, it continued apace in Scotland, with 400,000 Scots, 10 per cent of the population, estimated to have left the country between 1921 and 1931.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] When the Great Depression hit in the 1930s there were no easily available jobs in the US and Canada, and emigration fell to less than 50,000 a year, bringing to an end the period of mass migrations that had opened in the mid-eighteenth century.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] This contributed to the growth of the population, which reached a peak of 5,240,800 in 1974.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] There was also a decrease in some urban populations as a result of slum clearance, overspill and relocation to new towns, with the population of Glasgow falling from over a million in 1951 to 629,000 in 2001.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] Rural areas also saw a loss of population, particularly the Highlands and Hebrides.
[src:demographic-history-of-scotland/demographic-history-of-scotland] In the early part of the twenty-first century Scotland saw a rise in its population to 5,313,600 (its highest ever recorded) at the 2011 census.
